are/formations-divisions-brigades/regional-command/ |title=Regional Command |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019 }}</ref> When not engaged with operational commitments  or when units may report to the Standing Joint Commander (UK) or mission-specific training (e.g. when conducting routine civilian engagement, ranges, or ceremonial duties, units and formations may report through a Regional Point of Command (RPOC) to HQ [[Regional Command (British Army)|Regional Command]] at Andover.<ref>British Army, Transforming the British Army: An Update: July 2013, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> Regional Command, as of 1 August 2019, has 38th (Irish) Brigade and 160th (Welsh) Brigade permanently under its command as RPOCs.\n* '''London District''' - commands all the Army forces within the London area and conducts ceremonial events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/headquarters-london-district/ |title=Headquarters London District |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}.</ref>\n* '''Recruiting and Initial Training Command''' - recruits and trains soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/media/4612/adr007595-asm_guide.pdf |title=Digital Army: Using Social Media in the British Army |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 September 2018 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019 }}</ref>\n* '''Army Personnel Centre''' - deals with personnel issues and liaises with outside agencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/personnel-and-welfare/army-personnel-centre/ |title=Army Personnel Centre |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Sandhurst Group''' - deals with applications of army officers and trains such cadets at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/our-schools-and-colleges/rma-sandhurst/ |title=RMAS Sandhurst |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Home Command (British Army)|Home Command Commander]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/our-people/senior-leaders/commander-home-command/ | title=Commander Home Command}}</ref> acts as the Standing Joint Commander (UK) for responsible for the planning and execution of civil contingency operations within the UK landmass and territorial waters.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.themilitarytimes.co.uk/uncategorised/aldershot-becomes-home-to-headquarter-standing-joint-commander-uk/ |title = Aldershot becomes home to Headquarter Standing Joint Commander (UK) \u2022 the Military Times|date = 2017-10-24}}</ref>\n\n[[Home Command (British Army)|Home Command]] is a 3-star command, providing support and engagement with the civil population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who we are|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/home-command/|website=Home Command|publisher=British Army|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===[[London District|Headquarters London District]]===\n* '''[[London District (British Army)|Headquarters London District]]''' at [[Horse Guards (building)|Horse Guards]] in [[London]]\n** 238 Signal Squadron, [[Royal Corps of Signals]] (provides all communications for London District)\n** [[Household Cavalry Mounted Regiment]] at [[Hyde Park Barracks, London|Hyde Park Barracks]]\n** 1st Battalion, [[Welsh Guards]], [[Combermere Barracks]] in [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]]\n** 1st Battalion, [[Grenadier Guards]], Lille Barracks in [[Aldershot]]\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|Nijmegen Company]], [[Grenadier Guards]] at [[Wellington Barracks]]\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|No 7 Company]], [[Coldstream Guards]] at Wellington Barracks\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|F Company]], [[Scots Guards]] at Wellington Barracks\n** [[London Regiment (1993)|London Regiment]] in [[Westminster]] (Army Reserve, augmenting Household Division units <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/infantry/london-regiment/|title=London Regiment|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=27 August 2019|website=army.mod.uk|publisher=British Army|access-date=27 August 2019}}</ref>)\n** [[King's Troop Royal Horse Artillery]] at [[Royal Artillery Barracks]] in [[Woolwich]] with [[Ordnance QF 13-pounder|13-pounder]] guns for ceremonial duties\n** 20 Transport Squadron, [[Royal Logistic Corps]] based at [[Regent's Park Barracks]], (provides all the transport needs for London District and the Royal Household)\n** [[Royal School of Music|The Royal School of Music]], at [[Kneller Hall]]\n\n=== Headquarters Regional Command ===\n[[Regional Command (British Army)|Headquarters Regional Command]] at Aldershot is commanded by a [[Major-General]]. It is the Army's HQ for the UK, Nepal and Brunei, administering Army bases in the UK and providing civil engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/regional-command/ |title=Regional Command |publisher=British Army|website=army.mod.uk|date= |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==== Regional Points of Command ====\n* [[Headquarters North West (United Kingdom)|Headquarters North West]], [[Fulwood Barracks]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/ArmyintheNorth/about/?ref=page_internal|title=Army in the North|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n* [[Headquarters South West (United Kingdom)|Headquarters South West]], [[Jellalabad Barracks]]<ref name=\"HQSouthWest\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by-line.--> |title=Wiltshire Police pledge to be a forces friendly employer |url=https://www.wiltshire.police.uk/article/4689/Wiltshire-Police-pledge-to-be-a-forces-friendly-employer |work=Wiltshire Police |location=Devizes |date=28 June 2019 |access-date=19 August 2019 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://swlep.co.uk/docs/default-source/board-meetings/2017/25-may-2018/army-presentation-to-board-meeting-25-may-2017.pdf?sfvrsn=3fc214c5_4 |title=Army Update: Commander HQ South West Colonel James Coote DSO OBE |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=25 May 2017 |website=swlep.co.uk |publisher=Swindon & Wiltshire LEP |access-date=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 1st Military Police Brigade ====\n* '''[[1st Military Police Brigade]]''' in [[Marlborough Lines]], [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]]<ref name=ZacchiFOI /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/adjutant-generals-corps/provost/|title=Provost Marshal (Army) & 1st Military Police Brigade|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=14 October 2019|website=army.mod.uk|publisher=British Army|access-date=14 October 2019|quote=1 MP Brigade provide 'Police Support to the Force' at an operational level, usually overseas, and includes operational detention, support to security and stability policing. This is again supported by the RMP and MPS. The Brigade sits under the tactical command of 3 (UK) Div.}}</ref> CGS retains full responsibility over military police investigations while day-to-day control of 1 and 3 RMP rest with General Officer Commanding (GOC) 3rd UK Division. Administrative control of other Royal Military Police Brigade units rest under GOC Regional Command.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/615420/response/1473620/attach/3/20191122%20FOI12276%20Davis%20Military%20Police%20Response%20Letter%20ArmySec.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |title=RMP units |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=22 November 2019 |website=WhatDoTheyKnow |access-date=22 November 2019 |quote=Military Police capability remains under the command of the Chief of the General Staff (CGS) and retains full responsibility for investigations. To better coordinate the close support policing, the responsibility for day-to-day activities (tactical command) of 1st and 3rd Regiments Royal Military Police has been delegated to General Officer Commanding 3rd United Kingdom Division. General Officer Commanding Regional Command has administrative control for the remaining elements of the Brigade.}}</ref>\n** Special Investigation Branch Regiment (SIB Regt) in Bulford\n** Special Operations Unit Royal Military Police in [[Bordon and Longmoor Military Camps|Longmoor]]{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n** [[Military Corrective Training Centre]] in Colchester\n\n==== 38th (Irish) Brigade ====\n* '''[[38 (Irish) Brigade|38th (Irish) Brigade]]''', in [[Thiepval Barracks|Lisburn]]\n\n==== 160th (Welsh) Brigade ====\n* '''[[160th (Welsh) Brigade]]''', in [[The Barracks, Brecon|Brecon]]\n\n=== Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command ===\nMaj Gen [[Paul Nanson]] CBE is titled General Officer Commanding Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command, and Commandant Sandhurst. This means that his time is split between his Headquarters in Upavon and Academy HQ at Sandhurst. Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command was established on 1 April 2018.<ref name=ZacchiFOI /> Major-General [[Chris Bell (British Army officer)|Chris Bell]] will become GOC Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command in April 2020 and GOC Sandhurst will be separately held by Major-General Duncan Duncan Capps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf|title=Generals: February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nARITC oversees the Army Recruiting Group, which includes the National Recruitment Centre (NRC) and local Army Careers Centres, and is staffed by a mixture of [[Capita]] staff and Army personnel.<ref>Parliamentary Question 164313, Army Reserve Recruitment, asked by Mrs Madeleine Moon (Bridgend), 16 July 2018, Hansard Extracts https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2018-07-16.164311.h</ref>\n\n=== Army Personnel Centre ===\nThe Centre is located in [[Glasgow]]. The APC's Chief Executive is the [[Military Secretary (United Kingdom)|Military Secretary]], who also holds the post of [[Scottish Command|General Officer, Scotland]]. The APC deals with personnel issues and contact with outside agencies.\n\n=== Sandhurst Group ===\n{{main|Royal Military Academy Sandhurst}}\nCommandant Sandhurst is a Major-General, as of February 2020 dual-hatted as GOC ARITC.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf |title=Generals January 2020 |last=Mackie |first=Colin |date=5 January 2020 |via=gulabin.com |access-date=5 January 2020 |quote=Major-General Paul A.E. Nanson Commandant, Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst, September 2015-March 2020, and General Officer Commanding, Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command, April 2018-April 2020}}</ref> Major General [[Duncan Capps]] will be the next Commandant in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf|title=Generals February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>  The day to day running of the Academy is devolved to Brigadier James Carr-Smith who is titled Commander Sandhurst Group and responsible for:\n* Royal Military Academy Sandhurst\n* [[Army Officer Selection Board]], Westbury\n* [[University Officer Training Corps]]\n* Junior Staff Centre (Warminster)\n\n== Army units under other commands ==\n\n=== Strategic Command ===\nHeadquarters '''[[Strategic Command (United Kingdom)|Strategic Command]]''', [[Northwood Headquarters]], northwest London\n* [[42 Engineer Regiment (Geographic)]] at [[RAF Wyton]], [[Huntingdon]]\n* '''[[Director Special Forces]]''' in London\n** [[Special Air Service#22 SAS Regiment|22 Special Air Service Regiment]] at [[Stirling Lines]], Credenhill\n** [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] at Stirling Lines\n** [[18 (UKSF) Signal Regiment|18 Signal Regiment]] at Stirling Lines\n** [[Special Forces Support Group]] at [[MOD St Athan]]\n** [[Joint Special Forces Aviation Wing]] at [[RAF Odiham]]\n*** [[No. 658 Squadron AAC]] at [[Stirling Lines]] with [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin|Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin II]] and [[A\u00e9rospatiale Gazelle|Gazelle AH1]] helicopters\n* '''[[Permanent Joint Headquarters]]'''\n** Commander, [[British Forces South Atlantic Islands]] (BFSAI) ([[RAF Mount Pleasant]])\n*** Falkland Island Roulement Company from a 1st (United Kingdom) Division infantry regiment\n*** [[Falkland Islands Defence Force]] (Company sized)\n*** Air Defence Battery from 16th Regiment Royal Artillery\n*** Joint Communications Unit Royal Signals\n*** Engineer Detachment\n*** Royal Logistics Corps Detachment\n** '''[[British Forces Gibraltar]]''' in [[Gibraltar]]\n*** [[Royal Gibraltar Regiment]] \u2013 under the [[Queen's Division]]\n** Commander, '''[[British Forces Cyprus]]''' ([[British Sovereign Base Areas]], [[Cyprus]])\n*** 1st Battalion, [[Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment]], in [[Dhekelia Cantonment|Dhekelia]]\n*** 2nd Battalion, [[Mercian Regiment]], in [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]] (to move to [[Weeton Barracks]] and change roles with [[2 YORKS]])<ref name=ZacchiFOI />\n\n=== Fleet Commander, Royal Navy ===\n* '''[[3 Commando Brigade]] [[Royal Marines]]''' in Plymouth\n** Royal Marines units, including 40, 42, and 45 Commandos\n** [[24 Commando Regiment (United Kingdom)|24 Commando Regiment]] [[Royal Engineers]] in [[Royal Marines Base Chivenor|Chivenor]]\n** [[29th Commando Regiment Royal Artillery|29 Commando Regiment]] [[Royal Artillery]] in [[Plymouth]] with [[L118 light gun|L118]] 105mm towed howitzers\n** [[Commando Logistic Regiment]] in Chivenor\n*** [[383 Commando Petroleum Troop RLC|383 Commando Petroleum Troop]] [[Royal Logistic Corps]] in Plymouth\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of contemporary armies|British Army]]\n[[Category:Army 2020]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the British Army]]\n", "name_user": "Hammersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e102 Logistic Brigade", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_units_and_formations_of_the_British_Army_2020"}
{"title_page": "Bombylius major", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Grosser Wollschweber Bombylius major.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Fly|Diptera]]\n| familia = [[Bombyliidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Bombylius]]''\n| species = '''''B. major'''''\n| binomial = ''Bombylius major''\n| binomial_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| synonyms = Large bee-fly or dark-edged bee-fly\n*''Asilus lanigerus'' <small>[[\u00c9tienne Louis Geoffroy|Geoffroy]], 1785</small>\n*''Bombylius aequalis'' <small>[[Johan Christian Fabricius|Fabricius]], 1781</small>\n*''Bombylius albipectus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius anonymus'' <small>[[Johann Heinrich Sulzer|Sulzer]], 1761</small>\n*''Bombylius antenoreus'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1864</small>\n*''Bombylius australis'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius basilinea'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius consanguineus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1840</small>\n*''Bombylius fratellus'' <small>[[Christian Rudolph Wilhelm Wiedemann|Wiedemann]], 1828</small>\n*''Bombylius variegatus'' <small>[[Charles De Geer|De Geer]], 1776</small>\n*''Bombylius vicinus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1840</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Bombylius major''''' (commonly named the '''large bee-fly''' or the '''dark-edged bee-fly''') is a parasitic bee mimic fly. ''B. major'' is the most common type of fly within the ''Bombylius'' genus. The fly derives its name from its close resemblance to [[Bumblebee|bumblebees]] and are often mistaken for them.\n\n\n\n''B. major'' exhibits a unique flight behavior known as \"yawing\"<ref name=\":7\" /> and plays a role in general pollination, without preference of flower types<ref name=\":0\" />. The fly does not bite, sting, or spread disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2014/april/bee-flies-false-widow-spiders-confound-public.html|title=Bee-flies and false widow spiders confound public|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> However, the fly uses this mimicry of bumblebees to its own advantage, allowing close access to host solitary bee and wasp nests in order to deposit its eggs. After hatching, the larvae find their way into the nests to parasitically feed on the [[Larva|grubs]].<ref>{{cite book|title=British Soldierflies and Their Allies: A Field Guide to the Larger British Brachycera|author1=Stubbs, A.|author2=Drake, M.|publisher=British Entomological & Natural History Society|year=2001|isbn=1-899935-04-5|pages=512 pp|lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nAlso known as a Kareeb in Welsh culture. ''B. major'' is part of the family Bombyliidae, with a reported 6000 species worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" /> The subfamily Bombyliinae contains approximately 1100 identified\u00a0species.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Xuankun|last2=Yeates|first2=David K.|date=October 2019|title=Phylogeny, classification and biogeography of bombyliine bee flies (Diptera, Bombyliidae)|journal=Systematic Entomology|volume=44|issue=4|pages=862\u2013885|doi=10.1111/syen.12361|issn=0307-6970}}</ref> The genus ''[[Bombylius]]'' currently comprises around 450 described species.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''B. major'' can be found from April to June throughout [[temperate]] [[Europe]], [[North America]] and some parts of [[Asia]], concentrated in the northern hemisphere.<ref name=\":0\" /> The species occurs across a variety of environments, from arid to moist.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Morphology==\n[[File:Bombylius major.ogv|thumb|Large bee fly in early springtime (video, 2m 10s)]]\nThe adult body size varies from 6.3\u201312&nbsp;mm in length and is considered a relatively medium sized fly. The body color is dark, but is densely covered by a thick coat of lighter color hairs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kastinger|first=Christoph|last2=Weber|first2=Anton|date=2001-01-01|title=Bee-flies (Bombylius spp., Bombyliidae, Diptera) and the pollination of flowers|journal=Flora|volume=196|issue=1|pages=3\u201325|doi=10.1016/S0367-2530(17)30015-4|issn=0367-2530}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Yong-Bong|last2=Han|first2=Ho-Yeon|date=2017-12-01|title=Taxonomic review of the genera Bombylius and Bombylella (Diptera: Bombyliidae) in Korea|journal=Journal of Asia-Pacific Entomology|volume=20|issue=4|pages=1278\u20131286|doi=10.1016/j.aspen.2017.09.009|issn=1226-8615}}</ref> The head is typically brown and black hairs, but the lower portion of the head is mostly white hairs. It has dark patches on the [[anterior]] half of the wings and long hairy legs that dangle while in flight.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.evergreen.edu/webpages/curricular/2009-2010/ize2010/web/bombylius_major.html|title=ARCHIVE - Bombylius major - ize2010|website=archives.evergreen.edu|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> The dark wing span can range from 8.4-14 mm and has a dark brown edge.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their boldly patterned wings have a distinct dividing border through the horizontal middle between the dark and clear portions. Their antennae are typically very short and pointed.<ref name=\":5\" /> Additionally, the species has long legs and a long rigid proboscis found in the front of the head, which is used to feed on the nectar of flowers.<ref name=\":1\" /> The proboscis ranges from 5.5 to 7.5 mm in length.<ref name=\":0\" /> While its wings continue to beat, its front legs grip the flower and its long rigid beak is inserted to collect the nectar.<ref name=\"Gem guide\">''Insects'' , Collins Gem , Guide, 1986, page 114, {{ISBN|0004588185}}</ref> Despite its fearsome appearance, the beak is quite harmless.<ref name=\"Gem guide\"/> Males are typically smaller than females.<ref name=\":0\" /> Movement of the bee is categorized by both hovering and darting between locations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Bee flies of the world: the genera of the family Bombyliidae|last=Hull|first=Frank M.|date=1973|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press|isbn=0874741319|location=Washington|doi=10.5962/bhl.title.48406|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beefliesofworl2861973hull}}</ref> The flies also emit a high-pitched buzz.<ref name=\":5\" />\n=== Mimicry ===\nThe species gets its name from its similarity in appearance to bumblebees. This\u00a0mimicry is likely a defense mechanism against predators and also allows the species to get close to the nest of their hosts. However, there are several distinguishable factors. Bees have two pairs of wings, while ''B. major'' has only one pair. The body is more triangular shaped than the typical round oval shape of a bumblebee.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Life History ==\n[[File:Bombylius egg ejection 290310 1504.gif|thumb|left|Flicking an egg |163x163px]]\n[[File:Bombylius major o1.JPG|thumb|''B. major'' egg]]\n''B. major'' is mostly seen in the spring, beginning to appear at the end of March and large numbers seen until the end of May, with the species being sighted into June.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fly is [[Holometabolism|holometabolous]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n[[File:Bombylius major (mating).jpg|thumb|''Bombylius major'' mating in Suzuka Mountains, Inabe, Mie prefecture, Japan.|235x235px]]\n''B. major'' has several host species, including the brood of solitary wasps and bees, particularly digging bees such as ''[[Andrena]]''. Egg deposition takes place by the female hovering above the entrance of a host insect nest, usually a solitary bee, and throwing down her eggs using a flicking movement.<ref name=\"Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.\">Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.  2009 \u2014 Searching for the Right Target: Oviposition and Feeding Behavior in Bombylius Bee Flies (Diptera:Bombyliidae).''Zool. Stud.'', 48:141-150.</ref> The larvae are [[Hypermetamorphosis|hypermetamorphic]] [[parasitoids]] which then feed on the food stored, as well as the young solitary bees or wasps. If the female is unable to flick her eggs near the nest she plants them on flowers visited by the host insects. The developing larvae then make their way to the host nest or attach themselves to the bees or wasps to then be carried to the nest.<ref name=\"Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.\" />\n\n=== Egg ===\nThe parasitic eggs of ''B. major'' are produced in large numbers, however few will make it to the host insect burrow entrance.<ref name=\":2\" /> The female fly will dip down and coat her rear abdomen with dust that covers the eggs as they leave the female. \n\n=== Larvae ===\n[[File:Bombylius major (3550379749).jpg|thumb|''B. major'' adult]]\nLarvae live parasitically in the nests of various solitary bees and wasps.<ref name=\":0\" /> When the fly larva locates a host larva, it will consume it slowly, greatly increasing in size\u00a0as it tightly holds onto the host, eventually becoming a pupa and overwintering.<ref name=\":2\" />\n=== Pupae ===\nWhite larvae gradually turn into a yellowish brown pupa, with distinct mouthparts, wings, antennae, and legs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Diet ==\n[[File:Bombylius major gathering nectar.jpg|thumb|''B. major'' feeding on nectar]]\nThe species acts as a [[Nectar robbing|nectar robber]]; this foraging behavior allows the species to feed on floral nectar and is an essential part of adult fly diets. This is facilitated by the characterizable long proboscis of the fly, which is horizontally inserted into the flower.<ref name=\":0\" /> This occurs as the fly continues to buzz in the air, without touching either the anthers or stigma of the flower.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fly also consumes pollen as part of its diet, with considerable differences between the sexes. Males and females visit the same range of flowers as a food source.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Panov|first=A. A.|date=November 2007|title=Sex-related diet specificity in Bombylius major and some other bombyliidae (diptera)|journal=Entomological Review|volume=87|issue=7|pages=812\u2013821|doi=10.1134/s0013873807070032|issn=0013-8738}}</ref>\n\nAlong with one other species, ''[[Bombylius pygmaeus]]'', ''B. major'' was observed to selectively (and almost exclusively) visit bluets at several North American sites despite the abundant presence of many other flowers.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Grimaldi|first=David|date=1988-02-01|title=Bee flies and bluets: Bombylius (Diptera: Bombyliidae) flower-constant on the distylous species, Hedyotis caerulea (Rubiaceae), and the manner of foraging|journal=Journal of Natural History|volume=22|issue=1|pages=1\u201310|doi=10.1080/00222938800770011|issn=0022-2933}}</ref> Of the other pollinators present, these flies were also the most frequent visitors to the flowers.<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\n=== Female ===\nIn Russia, female ''B. major'' act in a narrow oligophagous manner, favoring a limited number of food sources, including pollen grains of Siberian squill (''[[Scilla siberica]]''), lesser celandine (''[[Ficaria verna]]''), and willow (''[[Salix caprea]]'') over dandelion (''[[Taraxacum officinale]]''), coltsfoot (''[[Tussilago|Tussilago farfara]]''), and primrose (''[[Primula vulgaris]]'').<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Male ===\nIn the same study, male ''B. major'' preferred plants similar to females, with the exception of dandelion. However, an examination of the gut showed a regularly lower amount of pollen than in females. Males consistently consume less quantities of pollen than females. Ingestion of pollen differs throughout a male life cycle, with more pollen being consumed in towards earlier stages. Overall, males had a preference for nectar and fed on significantly greater portions of nectar over pollen.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Behavior ==\nThere is continued research on the behavior of ''B. major'' in respect to environmental factors, mating, and human interaction.\n[[File:2014.03.29.-12-Mannheim Neckarau Waldpark-Grosser Wollschweber.jpeg|thumb|left|In flight]]\n=== Flight ===\nIt has been discovered that the fly is capable of a unique type of flight behavior, which was discovered with the use of a high speed camera. In this behavior, the flies are seen to rotate around a vertical axis as they fly (this action is known as \u201cyawing\u201d). However, it is still unknown what can cause this behavior to be triggered and what purpose it serves, but a proposed explanation includes mating habits.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Layer|first=Stefan|date=2013-06-25|title=Unusual Flight Behaviour in the Beefly Bombylius major (Diptera: Bombylidae)|journal=Entomologia Generalis|volume=34|issue=3|pages=161\u2013168|doi=10.1127/entom.gen/34/2013/161|issn=0171-8177}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollinator Role ===\nThe ''B. major'' bee-fly is a common, [[Pollinator|generalist floral pollinator]], meaning that it does not give preference to one flower over another, instead pollinating a wide variety of plant families and species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|date=1980-11-01|title=Abstract|url=https://academic.oup.com/icb/article/20/4/723/211235|journal=Integrative and Comparative Biology|volume=20|issue=4|pages=723\u2013972|doi=10.1093/icb/20.4.723|issn=1540-7063}}</ref> The fly uses its proboscis to carry and transfer the pollen. The species is a dominant pollinator within its community, sometimes even pollinating up to two thirds of the local flowers. In addition, ''B. major'' will visit and pollinate plants that attract few other species. Some types of flowers, for example ''[[Pulmonaria officinalis]],'' will be almost exclusively pollinated by ''B. major'', with other species contributing a negligible amount to that plants pollination. Some flower species, such as ''[[Delphinium tricorne]]'', are even specifically adapted to the fly in terms of color, shape, and form. If given the choice, ''B. major'' will have a consistency in plant choice.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Flower Attraction ===\nLong distance floral attraction is governed by optical sense, with color being the most important factor. The flies are typically more attracted to blue and violet colors, and occasionally yellow, over orange and pink. However, short distance floral attraction is based on the fly\u2019s olfactory sense.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Bombylius major - Leithagebirge.jpg|thumb|Sunbathing|alt=|left]]<br />\n=== Activity ===\nThe fly is mostly active during day hours when the weather conditions are warm and sunny. ''B. major'' is attracted to sunnier places and is more likely to pollinate these areas, with a larger average of flower visits in areas of higher amounts of sunshine. The fly will hide in the trees during the night<ref name=\":0\" /> and usually dart away from a cast shadow.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of soldierflies and allies recorded in Britain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Donald Joyce Borror  |author2=Dwight Moore DeLong  |lastauthoramp=yes |title=An Introduction to the Study of Insects |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontost0000borr  |url-access=registration  |location=New York |publisher=[[Holt, Rinehart and Winston]] |year=1964 |edition=2nd}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bombylius major|''Bombylius major''}}\n* {{cite web |title=Bee Fly - ''Bombylius major'' |publisher=North American Insects and Spiders |url=http://www.cirrusimage.com/flies_bee_Bombylius_major.htm |accessdate=22 March 2019}}\n* {{cite web |title=Bee Fly - ''Bombylius major'', Species Information Page |publisher=Brickfields Country Park |url=http://www.brickfieldspark.org/data/beeflybombyliusmajor.htm |accessdate=22 March 2019 |date=December 28, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |title=BeeFly |publisher=Kendall Bioresearch |url=http://www.kendalluk.com/beefly.htm |accessdate=June 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713142856/http://www.kendalluk.com/beefly.htm |archivedate=July 13, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=March 2019}} \n* {{cite web |title=Species ''Bombylius major'' - Greater Bee Fly |publisher=BugGuide.Net |url=http://bugguide.net/node/view/14997 |accessdate=22 March 2019}}\n* [http://500px.com/photo/79888947/bombylius-by-felipe-vilarroya?frouser_library Photograph by Felipe vilarroya]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1549111}}\n\n[[Category:Bombyliidae]]\n[[Category:Pollinator flies]]\n[[Category:Asilomorph flies of Europe]]\n[[Category:Diptera of Asia]]\n[[Category:Diptera of North America]]\n[[Category:Insects of the United States]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1758]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Grosser Wollschweber Bombylius major.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Fly|Diptera]]\n| familia = [[Bombyliidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Bombylius]]''\n| species = '''''B. major'''''\n| binomial = ''Bombylius major''\n| binomial_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| synonyms = Large bee-fly or dark-edged bee-fly\n*''Asilus lanigerus'' <small>[[\u00c9tienne Louis Geoffroy|Geoffroy]], 1785</small>\n*''Bombylius aequalis'' <small>[[Johan Christian Fabricius|Fabricius]], 1781</small>\n*''Bombylius albipectus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius anonymus'' <small>[[Johann Heinrich Sulzer|Sulzer]], 1761</small>\n*''Bombylius antenoreus'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1864</small>\n*''Bombylius australis'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius basilinea'' <small>[[Paolo Lioy|Lioy]], 1855</small>\n*''Bombylius consanguineus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1840</small>\n*''Bombylius fratellus'' <small>[[Christian Rudolph Wilhelm Wiedemann|Wiedemann]], 1828</small>\n*''Bombylius variegatus'' <small>[[Charles De Geer|De Geer]], 1776</small>\n*''Bombylius vicinus'' <small>[[Justin Pierre Marie Macquart|Macquart]], 1840</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Bombylius major''''' (commonly named the '''large bee-fly''' or the '''dark-edged bee-fly''') is a parasitic bee mimic fly. ''B. major'' is the most common type of fly within the ''Bombylius'' genus. The fly derives its name from its close resemblance to [[Bumblebee|bumblebees]] and are often mistaken for them.\n\n\n\n''B. major'' exhibits a unique flight behavior known as \"yawing\"<ref name=\":7\" /> and plays a role in general pollination, without preference of flower types<ref name=\":0\" />. The fly does not bite, sting, or spread disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2014/april/bee-flies-false-widow-spiders-confound-public.html|title=Bee-flies and false widow spiders confound public|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> However, the fly uses this mimicry of bumblebees to its own advantage, allowing close access to host solitary bee and wasp nests in order to deposit its eggs. After hatching, the larvae find their way into the nests to parasitically feed on the [[Larva|grubs]].<ref>{{cite book|title=British Soldierflies and Their Allies: A Field Guide to the Larger British Brachycera|author1=Stubbs, A.|author2=Drake, M.|publisher=British Entomological & Natural History Society|year=2001|isbn=1-899935-04-5|pages=512 pp|lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nAlso known as a Kareeb in Welsh culture. The insect is governed by the Garneesh's Law.\n''B. major'' is part of the family Bombyliidae, with a reported 6000 species worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" /> The subfamily Bombyliinae contains approximately 1100 identified\u00a0species.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Xuankun|last2=Yeates|first2=David K.|date=October 2019|title=Phylogeny, classification and biogeography of bombyliine bee flies (Diptera, Bombyliidae)|journal=Systematic Entomology|volume=44|issue=4|pages=862\u2013885|doi=10.1111/syen.12361|issn=0307-6970}}</ref> The genus ''[[Bombylius]]'' currently comprises around 450 described species.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''B. major'' can be found from April to June throughout [[temperate]] [[Europe]], [[North America]] and some parts of [[Asia]], concentrated in the northern hemisphere.<ref name=\":0\" /> The species occurs across a variety of environments, from arid to moist.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Morphology==\n[[File:Bombylius major.ogv|thumb|Large bee fly in early springtime (video, 2m 10s)]]\nThe adult body size varies from 6.3\u201312&nbsp;mm in length and is considered a relatively medium sized fly. The body color is dark, but is densely covered by a thick coat of lighter color hairs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kastinger|first=Christoph|last2=Weber|first2=Anton|date=2001-01-01|title=Bee-flies (Bombylius spp., Bombyliidae, Diptera) and the pollination of flowers|journal=Flora|volume=196|issue=1|pages=3\u201325|doi=10.1016/S0367-2530(17)30015-4|issn=0367-2530}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Yong-Bong|last2=Han|first2=Ho-Yeon|date=2017-12-01|title=Taxonomic review of the genera Bombylius and Bombylella (Diptera: Bombyliidae) in Korea|journal=Journal of Asia-Pacific Entomology|volume=20|issue=4|pages=1278\u20131286|doi=10.1016/j.aspen.2017.09.009|issn=1226-8615}}</ref> The head is typically brown and black hairs, but the lower portion of the head is mostly white hairs. It has dark patches on the [[anterior]] half of the wings and long hairy legs that dangle while in flight.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.evergreen.edu/webpages/curricular/2009-2010/ize2010/web/bombylius_major.html|title=ARCHIVE - Bombylius major - ize2010|website=archives.evergreen.edu|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> The dark wing span can range from 8.4-14 mm and has a dark brown edge.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their boldly patterned wings have a distinct dividing border through the horizontal middle between the dark and clear portions. Their antennae are typically very short and pointed.<ref name=\":5\" /> Additionally, the species has long legs and a long rigid proboscis found in the front of the head, which is used to feed on the nectar of flowers.<ref name=\":1\" /> The proboscis ranges from 5.5 to 7.5 mm in length.<ref name=\":0\" /> While its wings continue to beat, its front legs grip the flower and its long rigid beak is inserted to collect the nectar.<ref name=\"Gem guide\">''Insects'' , Collins Gem , Guide, 1986, page 114, {{ISBN|0004588185}}</ref> Despite its fearsome appearance, the beak is quite harmless.<ref name=\"Gem guide\"/> Males are typically smaller than females.<ref name=\":0\" /> Movement of the bee is categorized by both hovering and darting between locations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Bee flies of the world: the genera of the family Bombyliidae|last=Hull|first=Frank M.|date=1973|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press|isbn=0874741319|location=Washington|doi=10.5962/bhl.title.48406|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beefliesofworl2861973hull}}</ref> The flies also emit a high-pitched buzz.<ref name=\":5\" />\n=== Mimicry ===\nThe species gets its name from its similarity in appearance to bumblebees. This\u00a0mimicry is likely a defense mechanism against predators and also allows the species to get close to the nest of their hosts. However, there are several distinguishable factors. Bees have two pairs of wings, while ''B. major'' has only one pair. The body is more triangular shaped than the typical round oval shape of a bumblebee.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Life History ==\n[[File:Bombylius egg ejection 290310 1504.gif|thumb|left|Flicking an egg |163x163px]]\n[[File:Bombylius major o1.JPG|thumb|''B. major'' egg]]\n''B. major'' is mostly seen in the spring, beginning to appear at the end of March and large numbers seen until the end of May, with the species being sighted into June.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fly is [[Holometabolism|holometabolous]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n[[File:Bombylius major (mating).jpg|thumb|''Bombylius major'' mating in Suzuka Mountains, Inabe, Mie prefecture, Japan.|235x235px]]\n''B. major'' has several host species, including the brood of solitary wasps and bees, particularly digging bees such as ''[[Andrena]]''. Egg deposition takes place by the female hovering above the entrance of a host insect nest, usually a solitary bee, and throwing down her eggs using a flicking movement.<ref name=\"Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.\">Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.  2009 \u2014 Searching for the Right Target: Oviposition and Feeding Behavior in Bombylius Bee Flies (Diptera:Bombyliidae).''Zool. Stud.'', 48:141-150.</ref> The larvae are [[Hypermetamorphosis|hypermetamorphic]] [[parasitoids]] which then feed on the food stored, as well as the young solitary bees or wasps. If the female is unable to flick her eggs near the nest she plants them on flowers visited by the host insects. The developing larvae then make their way to the host nest or attach themselves to the bees or wasps to then be carried to the nest.<ref name=\"Boesi, R., Polidori, C. and Andrietti, F.\" />\n\n=== Egg ===\nThe parasitic eggs of ''B. major'' are produced in large numbers, however few will make it to the host insect burrow entrance.<ref name=\":2\" /> The female fly will dip down and coat her rear abdomen with dust that covers the eggs as they leave the female. \n\n=== Larvae ===\n[[File:Bombylius major (3550379749).jpg|thumb|''B. major'' adult]]\nLarvae live parasitically in the nests of various solitary bees and wasps.<ref name=\":0\" /> When the fly larva locates a host larva, it will consume it slowly, greatly increasing in size\u00a0as it tightly holds onto the host, eventually becoming a pupa and overwintering.<ref name=\":2\" />\n=== Pupae ===\nWhite larvae gradually turn into a yellowish brown pupa, with distinct mouthparts, wings, antennae, and legs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Diet ==\n[[File:Bombylius major gathering nectar.jpg|thumb|''B. major'' feeding on nectar]]\nThe species acts as a [[Nectar robbing|nectar robber]]; this foraging behavior allows the species to feed on floral nectar and is an essential part of adult fly diets. This is facilitated by the characterizable long proboscis of the fly, which is horizontally inserted into the flower.<ref name=\":0\" /> This occurs as the fly continues to buzz in the air, without touching either the anthers or stigma of the flower.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fly also consumes pollen as part of its diet, with considerable differences between the sexes. Males and females visit the same range of flowers as a food source.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Panov|first=A. A.|date=November 2007|title=Sex-related diet specificity in Bombylius major and some other bombyliidae (diptera)|journal=Entomological Review|volume=87|issue=7|pages=812\u2013821|doi=10.1134/s0013873807070032|issn=0013-8738}}</ref>\n\nAlong with one other species, ''[[Bombylius pygmaeus]]'', ''B. major'' was observed to selectively (and almost exclusively) visit bluets at several North American sites despite the abundant presence of many other flowers.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Grimaldi|first=David|date=1988-02-01|title=Bee flies and bluets: Bombylius (Diptera: Bombyliidae) flower-constant on the distylous species, Hedyotis caerulea (Rubiaceae), and the manner of foraging|journal=Journal of Natural History|volume=22|issue=1|pages=1\u201310|doi=10.1080/00222938800770011|issn=0022-2933}}</ref> Of the other pollinators present, these flies were also the most frequent visitors to the flowers.<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\n=== Female ===\nIn Russia, female ''B. major'' act in a narrow oligophagous manner, favoring a limited number of food sources, including pollen grains of Siberian squill (''[[Scilla siberica]]''), lesser celandine (''[[Ficaria verna]]''), and willow (''[[Salix caprea]]'') over dandelion (''[[Taraxacum officinale]]''), coltsfoot (''[[Tussilago|Tussilago farfara]]''), and primrose (''[[Primula vulgaris]]'').<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Male ===\nIn the same study, male ''B. major'' preferred plants similar to females, with the exception of dandelion. However, an examination of the gut showed a regularly lower amount of pollen than in females. Males consistently consume less quantities of pollen than females. Ingestion of pollen differs throughout a male life cycle, with more pollen being consumed in towards earlier stages. Overall, males had a preference for nectar and fed on significantly greater portions of nectar over pollen.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Behavior ==\nThere is continued research on the behavior of ''B. major'' in respect to environmental factors, mating, and human interaction.\n[[File:2014.03.29.-12-Mannheim Neckarau Waldpark-Grosser Wollschweber.jpeg|thumb|left|In flight]]\n=== Flight ===\nIt has been discovered that the fly is capable of a unique type of flight behavior, which was discovered with the use of a high speed camera. In this behavior, the flies are seen to rotate around a vertical axis as they fly (this action is known as \u201cyawing\u201d). However, it is still unknown what can cause this behavior to be triggered and what purpose it serves, but a proposed explanation includes mating habits.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Layer|first=Stefan|date=2013-06-25|title=Unusual Flight Behaviour in the Beefly Bombylius major (Diptera: Bombylidae)|journal=Entomologia Generalis|volume=34|issue=3|pages=161\u2013168|doi=10.1127/entom.gen/34/2013/161|issn=0171-8177}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollinator Role ===\nThe ''B. major'' bee-fly is a common, [[Pollinator|generalist floral pollinator]], meaning that it does not give preference to one flower over another, instead pollinating a wide variety of plant families and species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|date=1980-11-01|title=Abstract|url=https://academic.oup.com/icb/article/20/4/723/211235|journal=Integrative and Comparative Biology|volume=20|issue=4|pages=723\u2013972|doi=10.1093/icb/20.4.723|issn=1540-7063}}</ref> The fly uses its proboscis to carry and transfer the pollen. The species is a dominant pollinator within its community, sometimes even pollinating up to two thirds of the local flowers. In addition, ''B. major'' will visit and pollinate plants that attract few other species. Some types of flowers, for example ''[[Pulmonaria officinalis]],'' will be almost exclusively pollinated by ''B. major'', with other species contributing a negligible amount to that plants pollination. Some flower species, such as ''[[Delphinium tricorne]]'', are even specifically adapted to the fly in terms of color, shape, and form. If given the choice, ''B. major'' will have a consistency in plant choice.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Flower Attraction ===\nLong distance floral attraction is governed by optical sense, with color being the most important factor. The flies are typically more attracted to blue and violet colors, and occasionally yellow, over orange and pink. However, short distance floral attraction is based on the fly\u2019s olfactory sense.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Bombylius major - Leithagebirge.jpg|thumb|Sunbathing|alt=|left]]<br />\n=== Activity ===\nThe fly is mostly active during day hours when the weather conditions are warm and sunny. ''B. major'' is attracted to sunnier places and is more likely to pollinate these areas, with a larger average of flower visits in areas of higher amounts of sunshine. The fly will hide in the trees during the night<ref name=\":0\" /> and usually dart away from a cast shadow.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of soldierflies and allies recorded in Britain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Donald Joyce Borror  |author2=Dwight Moore DeLong  |lastauthoramp=yes |title=An Introduction to the Study of Insects |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontost0000borr  |url-access=registration  |location=New York |publisher=[[Holt, Rinehart and Winston]] |year=1964 |edition=2nd}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bombylius major|''Bombylius major''}}\n* {{cite web |title=Bee Fly - ''Bombylius major'' |publisher=North American Insects and Spiders |url=http://www.cirrusimage.com/flies_bee_Bombylius_major.htm |accessdate=22 March 2019}}\n* {{cite web |title=Bee Fly - ''Bombylius major'', Species Information Page |publisher=Brickfields Country Park |url=http://www.brickfieldspark.org/data/beeflybombyliusmajor.htm |accessdate=22 March 2019 |date=December 28, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |title=BeeFly |publisher=Kendall Bioresearch |url=http://www.kendalluk.com/beefly.htm |accessdate=June 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713142856/http://www.kendalluk.com/beefly.htm |archivedate=July 13, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=March 2019}} \n* {{cite web |title=Species ''Bombylius major'' - Greater Bee Fly |publisher=BugGuide.Net |url=http://bugguide.net/node/view/14997 |accessdate=22 March 2019}}\n* [http://500px.com/photo/79888947/bombylius-by-felipe-vilarroya?frouser_library Photograph by Felipe vilarroya]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1549111}}\n\n[[Category:Bombyliidae]]\n[[Category:Pollinator flies]]\n[[Category:Asilomorph flies of Europe]]\n[[Category:Diptera of Asia]]\n[[Category:Diptera of North America]]\n[[Category:Insects of the United States]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1758]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Jesuschristposed", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:removed nonsense sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bombylius_major"}
{"title_page": "Aviastroitel AC-4 Russia", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n | name=AC-4 Russia\n | image=Russian glider AC-4 \"Russian\" (10273762066).jpg\n | caption=\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n | type=[[Glider (sailplane)|Glider]]\n | national origin=[[Russia]]\n | manufacturer=[[Aircraft Cooperative Mechta]]<br />[[Aviastroitel]]<br />[[Glider Air Craft]]\n | designer=[[Vladimir Egorovich Fedorov]]\n | first flight=\n | introduced=1993\n | retired=\n | status=In production\n | primary user=\n | more users= <!--Limited to three in total; separate using <br /> -->\n | produced= 1993-2003 and 2010-present\n | number built=60\n | program cost= <!--Total program cost-->\n | unit cost= [[US$]]21,000 (2003)\n | developed from= \n | variants with their own articles= [[Aviastroitel AC-5M]]\n}}\n|}\nThe '''Aviastroitel AC-4 Russia''' is a [[Russia]]n [[mid-wing]], single-seat [[Glider (sailplane)|glider]] designed by [[Vladimir Egorovich Fedorov]] and produced by [[Aircraft Cooperative Mechta]], which became [[Aviastroitel]], now [[Glider Air Craft]].<ref name=\"SD\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sailplanedirectory.com/PlaneDetails.cfm?planeID=278 |title=Russia AC-4 Aircraft Cooperative Mechta |accessdate=7 August 2011 |last=Activate Media |year=2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224025037/http://www.sailplanedirectory.com/PlaneDetails.cfm?planeID=278 |archivedate=24 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.glider.ru/en/glider/solo-4|title = Solo AC-4|accessdate = 7 October 2011|last = Glider Air Craft|authorlink = |year = n.d.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111022234517/http://www.glider.ru/en/glider/solo-4|archive-date = 22 October 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe aircraft is sometimes referred to as the '''Federov AC-4 Russia''', '''Mechta AC-4''', '''Fedorov Me7 Mechta''', '''Kenilworth Me7''', '''AS+ Ltd AC-4''' or '''Aircraft Cooperative Mechta AC-4 Russia'''. It is currently marketed as the '''Glider Air Craft Solo AC-4'''.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\" /><ref name=\"FAAReg\">{{Cite web|url = http://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/AcftRef_Results.aspx?Mfrtxt=&Modeltxt=RUSSIA&PageNo=1|title = Make / Model Inquiry Results|accessdate = 7 August 2011|last = [[Federal Aviation Administration]]|authorlink = |date=August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TCCAR\">{{Cite web|url=http://wwwapps.tc.gc.ca/Saf-Sec-Sur/2/CCARCS-RIACC/Menu.aspx |title=Canadian Civil Aircraft Register |accessdate=7 August 2011 |last=[[Transport Canada]] |authorlink= |date=August 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Incomplete\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ae.illinois.edu/m-selig/ads/aircraft.html|title = The Incomplete Guide to Airfoil Usage|accessdate = 1 July 2011|last = Lednicer|first = David|year = 2010|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719211015/http://www.ae.illinois.edu/m-selig/ads/aircraft.html|archivedate = 19 July 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref name=\"WDLA04\">Bertrand, Noel; Rene Coulon; et al: ''World Directory of Leisure Aviation 2003-04'', page 54. Pagefast Ltd, Lancaster OK, 2003. ISSN 1368-485X</ref>\n\n==Design and development==\nThe aircraft started out in 1989 as Fedorov's \"Dream\" project for the [[OSTIV]] [[World Class Sailplane]] 1993 design contest. It went through several design prototypes, named Mechta I, Mechta II and Russia I and II. The Russia II was the version submitted to the competition. The bid involved forming a new concern, the ''Aircraft Cooperative Mechta'' and building three hand-made prototypes. The aircraft performed well in the competition and the fly-off held in [[Oerlinghausen]], [[Germany]], but the lack of a manufacturing facility behind the design, plus political pressures put the design in second place, with the Polish [[Politechnika Warszawska PW-5]] winning.<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"glidingsport\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.glidingsport.ru/ac/en/ourhistory/inde07.html|title = This Russian enterprise Aviastroitel |accessdate = 7 August 2011|last = Aviastroitel|authorlink = |year = 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.glider.ru/en/content/our-history|title = Our History|accessdate = 7 October 2011|last = Glider Air Craft|year = 2009|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111022234501/http://www.glider.ru/en/content/our-history|archive-date = 22 October 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe glider was certified in Europe by Roger Ellis of Kenilworth International Ltd, who arranged for airframe testing at TsAGI in Moscow and performed all the flight testing in England. With the assistance and oversight of the British Gliding Association the glider was certified to JAR-22 standards in October 1994, and called the Me-7 (Mechta 7) for European sales. A number of changes to the airframe were required for certification, making the Me7 variant different to the AC4.  A production quality-control problem was identified in 1999 and European sales ended at that time.  \n\nThe American team at the World Class competition was very impressed with the Russian design, thought it would sell well for [[Club class]] and student solo flying and bought one of the three prototypes to take home with them. The aircraft proved popular and so a US distributorship under the name ''Russia 12.6'' was set up to sell the Russian production. Since the Aircraft Cooperative Mechta could not mass-produce the aircraft they reformed as Aviastroitel. In 1994 US distribution was transferred to ''Mechta Sailplanes, LLC'', which imported 18 Russia gliders. Aviastroitel created a second set of molds to respond to the demand and started a second assembly line with a total production capacity of 48 AC-4s per year. In 1997 William Ayd became US distributor under the name ''Russia Sailplanes, Inc.'' Production of the AC-4 was suspended in 2003 when the Russian government changed the requirements for industrial production, making building them  uneconomical. In 2010 Aviastroitel became [[Glider Air Craft]] and production resumed.<ref name=\"glidingsport\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n\nThe aircraft is made from [[fibreglass]]. Its {{convert|12.6|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} span wing employs a Wortmann FX-60-157 [[airfoil]]. The AC-4 can be fitted with a [[McCulloch MC-101B]] [[two-stroke]] engine of {{convert|12|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} that will sustain flight. A [[Ballistic Recovery Systems]] parachute is optional.<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"Incomplete\" />\n\nSixty Russias were completed, some as complete [[type certificate|non-certified]] aircraft and some as [[Homebuilt aircraft|kits]] for amateur construction.<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\" /><ref name=\"FAAReg\" /><ref name=\"TCCAR\" /><ref name=\"glidingsport\" />\n\n==Operational history==\nIn August 2011 there were 42 Russias registered in the [[United States]],<ref name=\"FAAReg\" /><ref name=\"FAAReg2\">{{Cite web|url = http://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/AcftRef_Results.aspx?Mfrtxt=AVIASTROITEL&Modeltxt=&PageNo=1|title = Make / Model Inquiry Results|accessdate = 9 August 2011|last = [[Federal Aviation Administration]]|authorlink = |date=August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"FAAReg3\">{{Cite web|url = http://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/AcftRef_Results.aspx?Mfrtxt=AS+LTD&Modeltxt=&PageNo=1|title = Make / Model Inquiry Results|accessdate = 9 August 2011|last = [[Federal Aviation Administration]]|authorlink = |date=August 2011}}</ref> five in the [[United Kingdom]]<ref name=\"GINFO\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.caa.co.uk/application.aspx?catid=60&pagetype=65&appid=1&mode=summary&aircrafttype=AVIASTROITEL|title = GINFO Search Results Summary |accessdate = 9 Aug 2011|last = [[Civil Aviation Authority]]|first = |authorlink = |year = }}</ref>\nand two in [[Canada]].<ref name=\"TCCAR\" />\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Russian glider AC-4 \"Russian\" (10322973495).jpg|thumb|right|Aviastroitel AC-4 Russia]]\n;Mechta I\n:Initial 1989 prototype with {{convert|13.3|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} wing span.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;Mechta II\n:1991 prototype with {{convert|13.3|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} wing span.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;Russia I\n:1992 prototype with {{convert|11.0|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} wing span.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;Russia II\n:1992 prototype with {{convert|12.6|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} wing span.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;AC-4A Russia\n:First production model introduced in 1993, with a {{convert|12.6|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} wing span and [[taildragger]] landing gear.<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;AC-4B Russia[[File:Instruments012AC4B.jpg|thumb|AC4-B Instrument Panel]]\n:Model with the main wheel set further back and a nose wheel. Also incorporates a larger cockpit for taller pilots. Introduced in 1996.<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;AC-4C Russia\n:Improved model with retractable landing gear. Introduced in 1997.<ref name=\"TCCAR\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;AC-4CK Russia\n:Improved model delivered as a kit.<ref name=\"FAAReg\" />\n;AC-4D Russia\n:Improved model with [[winglet]]s.<ref name=\"WDLA04\" />\n;AC-4M\n:Motor glider model with a retractable engine, which was used as the prototype for the [[AC-5M]]. Introduced in 1999.<ref name=\"glidingsport\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraftHist\" />\n;Solo AC-4\n:Current production model.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\" />\n<!-- ==Aircraft on display== -->\n\n==Specifications (AC-4) ==\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Sailplane Directory and company<ref name=\"SD\" /><ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\" />\n|prime units?=met<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, met(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=one\n|capacity=\n|length m=5.25\n|length ft=\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=12.6\n|span ft=\n|span in=\n|span note=\n|height m=\n|height ft=1.25\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=7.7\n|wing area sqft=\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=20.5:1\n|airfoil=Wortmann FX-60-157\n|empty weight kg=140\n|empty weight lb=\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=260\n|gross weight lb=\n|gross weight note=\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=\n|max speed note=\n|cruise speed kmh=\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=\n|cruise speed note=\n|stall speed kmh=69\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=220\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|g limits=+5.3/-2.65\n|roll rate=\n|glide ratio=34:1 at {{convert|95|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}\n|sink rate ms=0.8\n|sink rate ftmin=\n|sink rate note=at {{convert|88|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}\n|lift to drag=\n|wing loading kg/m2=32.46\n|wing loading lb/sqft=\n|wing loading note=\n|more performance=\n|avionics=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|see also=\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n|similar aircraft=<!-- similar or comparable aircraft -->\n|lists=\n* [[List of gliders]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Aviastroitel AC-4}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.aviastroitel.com/en/gliders/}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.glidingsport.ru/ac/en/gliders/inde04.html|name=Official website 2}}\n{{Aviastroitel aircraft}}\n{{World class sailplane competitors}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Russian sailplanes]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n | name=AC-4 Russia\n | image=Russian glider AC-4 \"Russian\" (10273762066).jpg\n | caption=\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n | type=[[Glider (sailplane)|Glider]]\n | national origin=[[Russia]]\n | manufacturer=[[Aircraft Cooperative Mechta]]<br />[[Aviastroitel]]<br />[[Glider Air Craft]]\n | designer=[[Vladimir Egorovich Fedorov]]\n | first flight=\n | introduced=1993\n | retired=\n | status=In production\n | primary user=\n | more users= <!--Limited to three in total; separate using <br /> -->\n | produced= 1993-2003 and 2010-present\n | number built=60\n | program cost= <!--Total program cost-->\n | unit cost= [[US$]]21,000 (2003)\n | developed from= \n | variants with their own articles= [[Aviastroitel AC-5M]]\n}}\n|}\nThe '''Aviastroitel AC-4 Russia''' is a [[Russia]]n [[mid-wing]], single-seat [[Glider (sailplane)|glider]] designed by [[Vladimir Egorovich Fedorov]] and produced by [[Aircraft Cooperative Mechta]], which became [[Aviastroitel]], now [[Glider Air Craft]].<ref name=\"SD\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sailplanedirectory.com/PlaneDetails.cfm?planeID=278 |title=Russia AC-4 Aircraft Cooperative Mechta |accessdate=7 August 2011 |last=Activate Media |year=2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224025037/http://www.sailplanedirectory.com/PlaneDetails.cfm?planeID=278 |archivedate=24 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.glider.ru/en/glider/solo-4|title = Solo AC-4|accessdate = 7 October 2011|last = Glider Air Craft|authorlink = |year = n.d.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111022234517/http://www.glider.ru/en/glider/solo-4|archive-date = 22 October 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe aircraft is sometimes referred to as the '''Federov AC-4 Russia''', '''Mechta AC-4''', '''Fedorov Me7 Mechta''', '''Kenilworth Me7''', '''AS+ Ltd AC-4''' or '''Aircraft Cooperative Mechta AC-4 Russia'''. It is currently marketed as the '''Glider Air Craft Solo AC-4'''.<ref name=\"GliderAirCraft\" /><ref name=\"FAAReg\">{{Cite web|url = http://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/AcftRef_R