{"title_page": "Royal ballet of Cambodia", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Khmer classical dance|similar genera of performing arts|Lakhon khol|and|Lakhon pol srey}}\n{{Dance drama of Southeast Asia\n|image   = [[Image:Dancers angkor wat.jpg|200px]]\n|caption = The dancers of King Sisowath during a visit to the ruins of Angkor Wat\n}}\n{{Contains Khmer text}}\nThe '''Royal ballet of Cambodia ''' ({{lang-km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}} - ''Robam Preah Reachtroap'') is a form of performing arts established in the [[Court (royal)|royal courts]] of [[Cambodia]] for the purpose of entertainment as well as ceremonial [[propitiation]].<ref name=\"Cravath1968\">[[#Cravath1968|Cravath 1968]]</ref> It is the dominant genre of dance theatre in Cambodia that features the classical dance style ({{lang-km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e}} - ''Robam Kbach Boran'').\n\nIt is performed during [[Public holidays in Cambodia|public occasions]] and ceremonies in Cambodia as well as among Cambodians in other countries.<ref group=\"unver.\"> Public performances of Cambodian classical dance occasionally appear in Cambodian news and Western news outlets as photographs and video footage. See, for example, editorial photographs on Norodom Sihamoni's coronation at <http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/DWF15-974435/traditional-dancers-perform-for-new-cambodian-king/>.</ref> Performances entail elaborately dressed dancers performing a slow and figurative set of gestures and poses meant to entrance the viewer. The repertoire includes dances of tribute or [[invocation]] and the enactment of traditional stories and [[epic poems]] such as the ''[[Ramayana]]''.\n\n== Etymology ==\n\nWestern names for this dance tradition, such as '''Cambodian court dance''', often make reference to the royal court, as the tradition was performed and maintained by attendants of the royal palaces.<ref>[[#Banham1995|Banham 1995]], p. 154, \"performers were wives, concubines, and relatives of the ruler\"</ref><ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]], p. 59 \"Cambodian court dance\"</ref> As a performing art, it is formally referred to as the '''Royal Ballet of Cambodia''' (''le Ballet royal du Cambodge'' in French) by [[UNESCO]], Cravath, Brandon, and others in the academic field,<ref name=\"UNESCO\">[https://ich.unesco.org/en/RL/royal-ballet-of-cambodia-00060 UNESCO: Royal ballet of Cambodia - Intangible Heritage]</ref><ref>[[#Cravath1968|Cravath 1968]] mentions a variation: \"Royal Cambodian Ballet\".</ref><ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]] mentions \"Royal Cambodian Ballet\".</ref> although this term may also refer to the National Dance Company of Cambodia. The term '''Khmer classical dance''' is also used alongside \"Royal Ballet of Cambodia\" in publications by UNESCO and the above-mentioned authors.<ref name=\"UNESCO\"/>\n\nIn Khmer, it is formally known as ''Robam Preah Reach Trop'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}, lit. \"dances of royal wealth\") or ''Lakhon Preah Reach Trop'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}, lit. \"theatre of royal wealth\").<ref group=\"unver.\">UNESCO mentions ''lakhaon preah reach troap'', while it is also written as '\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799' (''robam preah reach trop'') on websites of the government of Cambodia, including the Ministry of Culture and Fine Arts. For example, see:<{{cite web |url=http://www.nwhc.cambodia.gov.kh/kh/node/136 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928150850/http://www.nwhc.cambodia.gov.kh/kh/node/136 |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}></ref> It is also referred to as ''Lakhon Luong'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u17a0\u17d2\u179b\u17bd\u1784}}, lit. \"the king's theatre\").<ref>[[#Cravath1968|Cravath]]; romanized as ''lakhon lueng'' (\"the king's dancers\")</ref><ref name=\"Fletcher2001\">[[#Fletcher2001|Fletcher 2001]], p. 306</ref> During the [[Cambodian coup of 1970|Lon Nol regime]] of Cambodia, the dance tradition was referred to as ''Lakhon Kbach Boran Khmer'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e\u1781\u17d2\u1798\u17c2\u179a}}, lit. \"Khmer theatre of the ancient style\"), a term alienating it from its royal legacy.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/><ref>[[#Sasagawa2005|Sasagawa 2005]], p. 437</ref>\n\nKhmer classical dancers, as a whole, are frequently referred to as ''apsara dancers'' by [[laymen]]; this usage would be incorrect with the modern form of the dance, as the ''apsara'' is just one type of character among others in the repertoire. Regardless, the tradition's romanticized affiliation with the ''apsaras'' and ''devatas'' of the ruins of [[Angkor]] still persists.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Finial with dancing figure from Cambodia, Angkorian style, 10th century, HAA.JPG|thumb|right|200px|[[Angkor]]ian style dancing figures from the 10th century]]\n[[File:LePetitJournal 1906 06 24.jpg|thumb|200px|The ''kinnari'' dancers of King Sisowath at the 1906 Colonial Exposition in Marseilles]]\n\n'''Angkor and pre-Angkor era'''\n\nOne of the earliest records of dance in Cambodia is from the 7th century, where performances were used as a funeral rite for kings.<ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]], p. 20</ref> In the 20th century, the use of dancers is also attested in funerary processions, such as that for King [[Sisowath Monivong]]. During the [[Angkor]] period, dance was ritually performed at temples.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The temple dancers came to be considered as apsaras, who served as entertainers and messengers to divinities.<ref>[[#Becker1998|Becker 1998]], p. 330</ref> Ancient stone inscriptions, describe thousands of apsara dancers assigned to temples and performing divine rites as well as for the public.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The tradition of temple dancers declined during the 15th century, as the Siamese kingdom of [[Ayutthaya Kingdom|Ayutthaya]] raided Angkor. When Angkor fell, its artisans, Brahmins, and dancers were taken captive to Ayutthaya.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/>\n\n'''French colonial era'''\n\nDancers of the court of [[Sisowath of Cambodia|King Sisowath]] were exhibited at the 1906 Colonial Exposition in [[Marseilles]] at the suggestion of George Bois, a French representative in the Cambodian court.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\">[[#Jacobsen2008|Jacobsen]], p. 156</ref> Auguste Rodin was captivated by the Cambodian dancers and painted a series of water colors of the dancers. George Groslier, the French-colonial director of the Phnom Penh Mus\u00e9e Sarraut (today the National Museum), had 're-invented' large parts of the ballet through his studies of the bas-reliefs of Angkor Wat.<ref name=\"Falser2013\">Falser 2013</ref>\n\n'''Post-independent Cambodia'''\n\nQueen [[Sisowath Kosamak|Sisowath Kossamak]] became a patron of the Royal Ballet of Cambodia. Under the Queen's guidance, several reforms were made to the royal ballet, including choreography. Dance dramas were dramatically shortened from all-night spectacles to about one hour in length.<ref name=\"Sasagawa 2005\">[[#Sasagawa2005|Sasagawa 2005]]</ref> Prince [[Norodom Sihanouk]] featured the dances of the royal ballet in his films. \n \nThe dance tradition suffered setbacks during the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime, during which many dancers were put to death in the genocide.<ref group=\"unver.\">jumpcut.com [http://www.jumpcut.com/view/?id=426CF07C3EC311DB93291EE329CBD869. ''Cambodian Royal Court Dancing'']. Retrieved July 21, 2007. {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Although 90 percent of all Cambodian classical artists perished between 1975 and 1979 after the fall of the Khmer Rouge, those who did survive wandered out from hiding, found one another, and formed \"colonies\" in order to revive their sacred traditions.<ref group=\"unver.\">Alliance for California Traditional Arts [http://www.actaonline.org/grants_and_programs/apprenticeships/1999/shapiro.htm ''Classical Cambodian Dance Sophiline Cheam Shapiro and Socheata Heng'']. Retrieved July 21, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708150335/http://www.actaonline.org/grants_and_programs/apprenticeships/1999/shapiro.htm |date=July 8, 2007 }}</ref> Khmer classical dance training was resurrected in the refugee camps in eastern Thailand with the few surviving Khmer dancers. Many dances and dance dramas were also recreated at the [[Royal University of Fine Arts]] in Cambodia.\n\nIn 2003 it was inducted into the [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists]].\n\n== Performance ==\n\n[[File:Royal Ballet Camboda Apsara Mera.jpg|thumb|right|The Royal Ballet of Cambodia at curtain call (Paris, France 2010)]]\n\nDuring the era of the [[French protectorate of Cambodia|French Protectorate of Cambodia]] and before, it was customary for guests of the royal palace to receive a performance of the royal ballet.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\" /> In propitiation ceremonies ({{lang|km|\u1794\u17bd\u1784\u179f\u17bd\u1784}}, ''{{transl|km|buong suong}}''), it was performed at [[Wat Phnom]] and the [[Silver Pagoda]] and Throne Hall of the [[Royal Palace, Phnom Penh|Royal Palace]].<ref group=\"unver.\">This can be noted in vintage photographs and film. UNESCO's video presentation of the Royal Ballet of Cambodia depicts a modern-day propitiation ceremony at Wat Phnom.</ref> For entertainment, performances were often staged inside the pavilions of royal palaces.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\" /> In Phnom Penh, the Moonlight Pavilion was built for and is still used occasionally for classical dance performances. Nowadays, venues for performances by the Royal Ballet include the Chenla Theatre and the Chaktomuk Conference Hall, designed by architect [[Vann Molyvann]] during the [[Sangkum Reastr Niyum]] era.<ref group=\"unver.\">These venues have been mentioned on news reels on Cambodian news programs. See this article for an example: http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2011031447331/Lifestyle/discover-classic-dance-outdoors-by-chaktomuk.html</ref> Tourist restaurants in Cambodia, notably in [[Siem Reap]], also serve as venues for classical dance performances by amateur troupes.<ref group=\"unver.\">This can be seen in many photographs posted on Flickr and videos on Youtube. Restaurants include 'Jasmine Angkor' and 'Koulen'. Canby Publications has a section on this at <http://www.canbypublications.com/siemreap/srothersr.htm#PerformSR>.</ref>\n\n=== Stage and props ===\n\nThe traditional stage for classical dance drama performances contains a table with a decorative pillow, sometimes laid on an Oriental rug or carpet.<ref group=\"unver.\">As seen in this photograph: <https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5374895656/> and as depicted in other photographs and video.</ref> This table of low stature, called a ''krae'' ({{lang|km|\u1782\u17d2\u179a\u17c2}}, lit. \"bed\"), is constant throughout the performance and thus is used as a prop that represents many places and things (a bed, a throne, living quarters, etc.).<ref group=\"unver.\">Cravath romanizes this term as ''kr\u00e9''. In this photo of the Reamker [[:File:Cambodian dance Reamker.png]], parts of the ''krae'' can be seen behind the main group of dancers.</ref>\n\nIn many dance dramas, characters often wield weapons such as bows, swords, staves, and clubs.<ref group=\"unver.\">This is notable in many media provided by laymen online as well as photos provided in this article. See http://www.jiras.se/preahsamuth/index.html, which shows the dance drama Preah Samut and characters wielding bows and staves.</ref> In some dances, dancers hold items such as flower garlands, fans, and gold and silver flowers as a tribute (''see {{transl|ms|[[bunga mas]]}}'').<ref group=\"unver.\">See [File:Cambodian_Classical_Dance_of_Tribute.ogv] as an example where dancers hold gold flowers as a tribute.</ref> Performances of ''{{transl|km|robam makar}}'' (the [[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]] dance) entail devas dancing in leisure and using fans to represent the scales of the mythical makara while the goddess [[Manimekhala]] leads the mimicry with her crystal ball of magic.<ref group=\"unver.\">As seen in the Khmer classical dance video posted on this webpage: <http://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/dance/dance-spirit-cambodia> and many others.</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Cambodian_dance_Reamker.png|935px|A scene from the Reamker; a battle between Rama and Ravana performed in the courtyard of the Silver Pagoda, c. 1900s~1920s}}\n\n== Movement and gestures ==\n\nKhmer classical dancers use stylized movements and [[gesture]]s to convey meaning and tell a story. These gestures are often vague and abstract, though some may be easily understood. Dancers do not sing or generally speak, except in some dance dramas where there are brief instances of speech by the dancers.\n\nHand gestures in Khmer classical dance are called ''{{transl|km|kbach}}'' (meaning \"style\"). These hand gestures form a sort of alphabet and represent various things from nature such as fruit, flowers and leaves. They are used in different combinations and transitions with accompanying movement of the legs and feet to convey different thoughts and concepts.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The way gestures are presented, the position of the arm, and the position of the hand relative to the arm can affect their meaning. Gestures are performed in different manners depending on the character type.\n\n== Characters ==\n\n[[File:BupphaDeviDance.png|thumb|Princess [[Buppha Devi]] performs a propitiation dance (c. 1965) as a ''{{transl|km|neang rong}}''. Note the dancers of lower ranks (''{{transl|km|philieng}}'') in [[obeisance]].]]\n\nFour main types of roles exist in Khmer classical dance: ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}'' (male), ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' (female), ''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' (ogres or [[asuras]]), and the ''{{transl|km|sva}}'' (monkeys).<ref name=\"Bois\">[[#Bois|Bois]], p. 4</ref> These four basic roles contain sub-classes to indicate character rank; a ''{{transl|km|neay rong ek}}'', for example, would be a leading male role and a ''{{transl|km|neang kamnan}}'' (or ''{{transl|km|philieng}}'') would be a maiden-servant.<ref name=\"Bois\"/> The sub-classes of the four main roles all perform in the same type of dancing style of the class they belong to. However, the ''{{transl|km|yeakheney}}'', or female ogre, is performed with a feminized dancing style of the male counterpart. Other female character types, such as the apsara, kinnari, or mermaid, follow the same dancing style as the ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' role but with subtle differences in gestures; the main difference being costume. The ''{{transl|km|ngoh}}'' character type, although male, is presented with a different dancing style than the ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}''.\n\nMost roles are performed by female dancers, but the role of monkeys was transferred to men under the guidance of Queen Sisowath Kosssamak. Other roles performed by men include hermits and animals such as horses and mythical lions.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n'''''{{transl|km|Neay rong}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neay rong ek}}'' - deities, kings, or princes (e.g. [[Rama]])\n*''{{transl|km|Philieng ek}}'' - ''aide-de-camp'' of important characters\n*''{{transl|km|Sena ek}}'' - the generals\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Neang}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neang ek}}'' - deities, queens or princesses (e.g. [[Sita]] and [[Manimekhala]])\n*''{{transl|km|Neang rong}}'' - [[noblewomen]] or angels (e.g., the daughters of the tycoon, Sampov Keo and Sampov Meas in the dance drama: ''{{transl|km|Krai Thong}}'')\n*''{{transl|km|Philieng ek}}'' - female ''aid-de-camp'' (ex. {{transl|km|Sopheak Leak}})\n*''{{transl|km|Neang kamnan}}'' or ''{{transl|km|philieng}}'' - female servants or attendants\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Yeak}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Yeak ek}}'' - premiere ogres or asuras (e.g., [[Ravana]])\n*''{{transl|km|Yeak rong}}'' - the lesser ogres\n*''{{transl|km|Yeakheney}}'' - ogresses, [[yakkhini]] (e.g. [[Surpanakha]])\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Sva}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neay sva khen}}'' - monkey generals (e.g., [[Hanuman]])\n*''{{transl|km|Pouk khen sva}}'' - monkey soldiers\n\n'''Other character types'''\n*Apsaras - celestial nymphs\n*''{{transl|km|Kinnorey}}'' - the mythical [[kinnara|kinnaris]] (e.g. [[Manohara]])\n*''{{transl|km|Maccha}}'' - [[mermaid]]s (e.g., [[Suvannamaccha]])\n*''{{transl|km|Ngoh}}'' - a special masculine role depicting a [[negrito]]\n*''Eysey'' - hermits or [[rishi]], a non-dancing role\n*[[Porter (carrier)|Porters]] - involved loosely in the dance, generally does not dance\n\n'''Animals'''\n*[[Garuda]] and mythical birds (e.g. [[Jatayu]])\n*[[Deer]] - the Golden Deer in the ''Ramayana''\n*[[Peafowl]]\n*[[Lion]]s\n*[[Horse]]\n}}\n\n== Costume ==\n[[File:Apsara dance.jpg|thumb|right|[[Apsara]] dancer]]\nClassical dance costumes are highly ornate and heavily embroidered, sometimes including sequins and even semi-precious gems. Most of the costumes are thought to be representative of what divinities wear, as reflected in the art style of the post-Angkor period. Various pieces of the costume (such as shirts) have to be sewn onto the dancers for a tight fit.\n\n=== Female costume ===\n\nThe typical female, or ''{{transl|km|neang}}'', costume consists of a ''{{transl|km|[[sampot]] sarabap}}'' (or ''{{transl|km|charabap}}''), a type of woven fabric with two contrasting silk threads along with a metallic thread (gold or silver in color). The ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' is wrapped around the lower body in a sarong-like fashion, then [[pleated]] into a band in the front and secured with a gold or brass belt. In the current style, part of the pleated brocade band hangs over the belt on the left side of the belt buckle, which is a clear distinction from Thai classical dance costumes where this pleated band is tucked into the belt to the right of the belt buckle. Worn over the left shoulder is a [[shawl]]-like garment called a ''{{transl|km|[[sbai]]}}'' (also known as the ''{{transl|km|robang khnang}}'', literally \"back cover\"); it is the most decorative part of the female costume, embroidered extensively with tiny beads and sequins. The usual embroidery pattern for the ''sbai'' these days is a diamond-shaped floral pattern, but in the past there were more variations of floral patterns. Under the ''sbai'' is a silk undershirt or bodice worn with a short sleeve exposed on the left arm. Around the neck is an embroidered collar called a ''{{transl|km|srang kar}}''.\n\nJewelry for the female role includes a large, [[filigreed|filigree]] square pendant of which is hung by the corner, various types of ankle and wrists [[bracelets]] and [[bangle]]s, an [[arm ring|armlet]] on the right arm, and body chains of various styles.\n\n=== Male costume ===\n\nMale characters wear costumes that are more intricate than the females, as they require pieces, like sleeves, to be sewn together while being put on. They are dressed in a ''{{transl|km|sampot sarabap}}'' like their female counterpart; however, it is worn differently. For the male, or ''neay rong'', the ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' is worn in the ''{{transl|km|[[chang kben]]}}'' fashion, where the front is pleated and pulled under, between the legs, then tucked in the back and the remaining length of the pleat is stitched to the ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' itself to form a draping 'fan' in the back. Knee-length pants are worn underneath, displaying a wide, embroidered [[hem]] around the knees. For the top, they wear long-sleeved shirts with rich embroidering, along with a collar, or ''{{transl|km|srang kar}}'', around their neck. On the end of their shoulders are a sort of [[epaulette]] that arches upwards like [[Indra]]'s bow (known as ''{{transl|km|inthanu}}''). Other components of the male costumes are three richly embroidered banners worn around the front waist. The center piece is known as a ''{{transl|km|robang muk}}'' while the two side pieces are known as a ''{{transl|km|cheay kraeng}}''; monkeys and yaksha characters wear another piece in the back called a ''{{transl|km|robang kraoy}}''.\n\nMale characters also wear an X-like strap around the body called a ''{{transl|km|sangvar}}''; it may be made of gold-colored silk or chains of gold with square ornaments, the latter being reserved for more important characters. Males wear the same ankle and wrist jewelry as females, but with the addition of an extra set of bangles on the wrist and no armlets. They also wear a kite-shaped ornament called a ''{{transl|km|sloek po}}'' (named after the [[bo tree]] leaf), which serves as a center point for their ''{{transl|km|sangvar}}''.\n\n=== Headdress ===\n\nThere are several types of [[Crown (headgear)|crowns]] that denote characters' ranks. Commonly worn by female characters of the lowest rank is the ''{{transl|km|kbang}}''; it is also worn by Brahmin characters with ornaments around a bun of hair. [[Divinity|Divinities]] and royal characters of the highest ranks wear a tall single-spire crown called a ''{{transl|km|mokot ksat}}'' for male characters and a ''{{transl|km|mokot ksatrey}}'' for female characters. The ''{{transl|km|panchuret}}'' (Groslier romanizes this as ''{{transl|km|panntiereth}}''), reserved for princes and generals (''{{transl|km|sena}}''), is a circlet-like crown with a faux knot in the back. The ''{{transl|km|rat klao}}'' is worn by princesses and often by maidens of significance in a dance if they happen to not be of royal rank. Some characters' headdressings include ear ornaments as well as earrings. Characters such as ogres and monkeys wear masks. Ogres and monkeys of royal rank wear masks with a ''{{transl|km|mokot}}'' attached.\n\n=== Floral adornments ===\n\nDancers are traditionally adorned with fragrant flowers, although sometimes fresh flowers are substituted with faux flowers. The floral tassel is traditionally made of ''[[Jasminum sambac]]'' strung together with ''[[Michelia]]'' flowers, being either ''[[Michelia \u00d7 alba]]'' or ''[[Michelia champaca]]''. The ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' (female) role wears a rose above the right ear and a floral tassel attached to the left side of the crown while the ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}'' (male) role wears a rose on the left ear and a floral tassel to the right side. Sometimes, dancers will wear jasmine garlands fit for the wrists. The ''apsara'' role is most often adorned with the flowers of either ''[[Plumeria obtusa]]'' or white cultivars of ''[[Plumeria rubra]]''; sometimes plumerias are tied along the back of their hair.\n\n== Music ==\n{{main|Pinpeat}}\n{{listen \n | filename     = Khmer classical dance song.ogg\n | title        = Krai Thong\n | description  = A song from a scene in the dance drama Krai Thong.\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\n\nThe music used for Khmer classical dance is played by a pinpeat ensemble. This type of orchestra consists of several types of [[xylophones]], [[drum]]s, [[oboe]]s, [[gong]]s, and other [[musical instrument]]s. The chorus consists of several singers who mainly sing in the absence of music. The lyrics are in poetry form and are sung interspersed with the grammatical particles eu [\u0259\u02d0], eung [\u0259\u02d0\u014b], and euy [\u0259\u02d0j] in various patterns.\n\n=== Musical instruments ===\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat ek]]}}'' : The lead xylophone with bamboo or teak wood keys\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat thung]]}}'' : A xylophone with bamboo or teak wood keys; low\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat dek]]}}'' : A metallophone of brass keys\n*''{{transl|km|Roneat thong}}'' : A metallophone (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|[[Kong thom]]}}'' : A set of 16 gongs arranged in a circle\n*''{{transl|km|[[Kong toch]]}}'' : Like the gongs above, but smaller\n*''{{transl|km|[[Chhing]]}}'' : A pair of finger cymbals\n*''{{transl|km|Krap}}'' : A pair of wood clappers (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|[[Sralai]]}}'' : A type of shawm; there are two sizes\n*''{{transl|km|[[Khloy]]}}'' : A type of flute made from bamboo (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|Skor thom}}'' : A pair of drums played with a percussion mallet\n*''{{transl|km|[[Sampho]]}}'' : A type of drum played with the hands\n}}\n\n=== Music pieces ===\nKhmer classical dance uses particular pieces of music for certain events, such as when a dancer enters or leaves a scene, or performs certain actions, such as flying or walking. These musical pieces are arranged to form a suite. New pieces of music are rarely created.\n\nBelow is a select list of music pieces used in the repertoire:\n\n*''{{transl|km|Sathukar}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17b6\u1792\u17bb\u1780\u17b6\u179a}}) a song of blessing used for [[propitiation]], often used to commence a performance\n*''{{transl|km|Krao nai}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179a\u17c5\u178e\u17c3}}), also known as ''{{transl|km|santheuk knong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u1793\u17d2\u1792\u17b9\u1780\u1780\u17d2\u1793\u17bb\u1784}}), overture of the ''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' (ogre) characters, a display of power as they go into [[combat]] or battle\n*''{{transl|km|Smaeu}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17d2\u1798\u17be}}) used for the introduction of a character or a group of dancers in a scene\n*''{{transl|km|Lea}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17b6}}) used to present a character's departure from the scene; leaving the [[stage (theatre)|stage]]\n*''{{transl|km|Cheut chhing}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1787\u17be\u178f\u1788\u17b7\u1784}}) lit., [[euphonic]] ''{{transl|km|[[chhing]]}}''; music characterized by the constant percussion of drums and small cup-shaped cymbals;<ref group=\"unver.\">Robert K. Headley 1997, ''Cambodian-English Dictionary''</ref> used to present an action such as commencing a journey or flying\n*''{{transl|km|Lo}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17c4}}) music used in tune with aquatic recreation (e.g. dancers miming the action of [[Watercraft rowing|rowing a boat]])\n*''{{transl|km|Long song mon}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u1784\u179f\u17ca\u1784\u1798\u1793}}) lit., \"royal bathing of the [[Mon people|Mon]]\"; a song used to represent a character dressing up their appearance\n*''{{transl|km|Phya deun}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1795\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u178c\u17be\u1793}}); also known as ''{{transl|km|ponhea daeur}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u1789\u17d2\u1789\u17b6\u178a\u17be\u179a}}), a music piece used to present dancers marching (e.g. the beginning of ''{{transl|km|robam tep monorom}}'')\n*''{{transl|km|Klom}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179b\u17bb\u1798}}) used to show the grace and beauty of a character wielding his weapon\n*''{{transl|km|Sinuon}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17ca\u17b8\u1793\u17bd\u1793}}) - lit., \"cream color\", in reference to complexion, a soft and slow feminine melody\n*''{{transl|km|Salamar}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u179b\u1798\u17b6\u179a}}) - a music characterized by the ''{{transl|km|sralai}}'', often used for certain actions such as combat, but not limited to such\n*''{{transl|km|Preah Thong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u1790\u17c4\u1784}})\n*''{{transl|km|Bao Lut}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1794\u17c4\u179b\u17bb\u178f}})\n*''{{transl|km|Sarak Burong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u179a\u17c8\u1794\u17ca\u17bb\u179a\u1784}})\n*''{{transl|km|Balim}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1794\u179b\u17b7\u1798}})\n\n== Repertoire ==\n\nAccording to ''The Cambridge Guide to Asian Theatre'' (1997), the Royal Ballet's repertoire contained approximately 40 dances and 60 dance dramas. Since the restoration of the Royal Ballet in the 1979, some of the old repertoire was recreated and several new dances were also created, most notably ''robam monosanhchettana'' by the late Chea Samy. As of recent years, new dance dramas have been created by the Royal Ballet, such as ''Apsara Mera''. [[Sophiline Cheam Shapiro]] has also introduced new repertory to Khmer classical dance, although they are not part of the traditional royal repertoire and mainly have been performed in Western venues. Her works include dramas such as ''{{transl|km|Samritechak}}'', an adaptation of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Othello]]'' and ''{{transl|km|Pamina Devi}}'', an adaptation of [[Mozart]]'s ''[[The Magic Flute]]''.\n\n=== Dance dramas ===\n\nThe repertoire of dance dramas ({{lang|km|\u179a\u17bf\u1784}}, ''{{transl|km|roeung}}'') consists of a myriad of stories, unlike the ''{{transl|km|lakhon khol}}'', which is limited only to the ''Ramayana''. Many of the dance dramas have analogs in the ''lakhon nai'' dance genre of Thailand but do not share the same choreography or exact storyline. During the time of Queen Kossamak, several dance dramas were re-choreographed and shortened such as ''[[Preah Thong and Neang Neak|Roeung Preah Thong-Neang Neak]]''; this drama, among others, would be recreated in 2003.\n\nThe plots of many dance dramas often concern a male character who rescues a [[damsel in distress]] or destined love presented with obstacles. The traditional repertoire portrays mythology or traditional tales and may sometimes include religious concepts such as [[karma]].\n\n[[File:Cambodian Classical Dance of Tribute.ogv|thumb|400px|A dance of tribute used in a dance drama titled ''Preah Ket Mealea'', circa 1965]]\n\n==== Select repertory of dance dramas ====\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''{{transl|km|[[Reamker]]}}'' (''Ramakerti'', {{lang|km|\u179a\u17b6\u1798\u1780\u17c1\u179a\u17d2\u178f\u17b7\u17cd}}): Ramayana\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Sothon-Neang Monorea}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u17bc\u1792\u1793-\u1793\u17b6\u1784\u1798\u1793\u17c4\u17a0\u17cd\u179a\u17b6}}): Sudhana-Jataka, formerly referred to as ''{{transl|km|Kailas}} ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17c3\u179b\u17b6\u179f}}), recreated in 2003\n* ''{{transl|km|Krai Thong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1790\u17c4\u1784}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Inao}}'' ({{lang|km|\u17a5\u178e\u17b6\u179c}}): [[Panji (prince)|Panji]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Kakey}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17b6\u1780\u17b8}}): Kakati-Jataka\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Anoruth-Neang Usa}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u17a2\u1793\u17bb\u179a\u17bb\u1791\u17d2\u1792-\u1793\u17b6\u1784\u17a7\u179f\u17b6}}): [[Aniruddha]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Sopheak Leak}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17bb\u1797\u179b\u1780\u17d2\u1781\u178e\u17cd}}): [[Chitralekha (deity)|Chitralekha]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Samot}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u1798\u17bb\u1791\u17d2\u179a}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Sovannahong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17bb\u179c\u178e\u17d2\u178e\u17a0\u1784\u17d2\u179f}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Sang}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u17d0\u1784\u17d2\u1781}})\n}}\n\n=== Dances ===\n\nIn contrast to the dance dramas are shorter dances known as ''{{transl|km|robam}}''. They can serve several purposes, such as honoring, ritualistic functions (e.g. securing the kingdom's fortune and prosperity), and blessing. Spanning several minutes or so, not all these dances have storylines, although many ''robam'' are indeed excerpts from dance dramas such as ''{{transl|km|robam mekhala-reamso}}'' and ''{{transl|km|robam sovan macchha}}'' (the latter being from the ''{{transl|km|Reamker}}'').\n\nThe 'apsara dance' of today was created under the guidance of Queen Kossamak Nearireath. Its costume is based on the [[bas-relief]] of ''apsaras'' on temple ruins but much of it, including its music and gesture, is not unique from other classical Khmer dances that probably do not date back to the [[Angkor]] period.\n\n==== Select repertory of dances ====\n\n* [[Apsara Dance|Robam Apsara]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u17a2\u1794\u17d2\u179f\u179a\u17b6)\n* [[Robam Tep Monorom]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1791\u17c1\u1796\u1798\u1793\u17c4\u179a\u1798\u17d2\u1799)\n* [[Robam Chun Por]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1787\u17bc\u1793\u1796\u179a)\n* [[Robam Makar]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1798\u1780\u179a)\n* [[Robam Sovann Maccha]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u179f\u17bb\u179c\u178e\u17d2\u178e\u1798\u1785\u17d2\u1786\u17b6)\n* [[Robam Moni Mekhala]] or Mekhala-Reamesor (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1798\u178e\u17b8\u1798\u17c1\u1781\u179b\u17b6)\n\n== Glossary ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n;''{{transl|km|kbach}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785}}) : (lit., \"style\" or \"motif\") referring to a pose or gesture used in Khmer classical dance\n;''{{transl|km|lakhon}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793}}) : (lit., \"theatre\"; also romanized as ''lakhaon'' and ''lkhaon''), referring to different genres of theatrical performances\n;''{{transl|km|lakhon preah reach trop}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}): (lit., \"theatre of royal wealth\") the Khmer name for the main classical dance drama of Cambodia; the royal ballet of Cambodia, in this case, the term ''lakhon'' may be substituted with ''robam''\n;''{{transl|km|robam}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6}}) : (lit., \"dance\"), a term used to refer to dances and in some contexts, all classical dances\n;''{{transl|km|robam kbach boran}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e}}): (lit., \"dance of the ancient style\") a term referring to classical dance that is used in the genres of theatre including ''{{transl|km|lakhon khol}}'', ''{{transl|km|lakhon pol srey}}'', and ''{{transl|km|lakhon preah reach trop}}''. Not to be confused with the term devised in the Lon Nol era.\n;''{{transl|km|roeung}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u17c0\u1784}}) : (lit., \"story\"); referring to dance dramas\n;''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1799\u1780\u17d2\u1781}}) : [[yaksha]]; a class of characters representing [[asuras]] and [[ogres]], commonly translated as \"giants\"\n}}\n\n== Media ==\n\n=== Gallery ===\n{{Commons category multi|Khmer classical dance|Royal Ballet of Cambodia}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:BupphaDeviDancing.png|[[Norodom Buppha Devi|Princess Buppha Devi]] performs a dance in [[Royal Palace of Cambodia|Cambodian Royal Palace]].\nFile:Indra Silver Pagoda Mural.jpg|A mural depiction of Indra and his dancers, [[Silver Pagoda, Phnom Penh|Silver Pagoda]], Cambodian Royal Palace.\nFile:Cambodiacourtdance.gif| Royal dance troupe of [[Sisowath of Cambodia|King Sisowat]], early 1900s. \nFile:Sita Ravana Cambodia.jpg|[[Sita|SIta]] and [[Ravana]] performs in a scene of [[Reamker]] dance drama.\n</gallery>\n\n{{ external media\n| align  = right\n| image1 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5630277276/ Two dancers perform as a garuda and kinnari couple. (1928)]\n| image2 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5374895656/ A pair of dancers sit on a ''krae''. (1931)]\n| image3 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5629694471/ Ravana with Sita in his captive. (1928)]\n| image4 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5630278044/ A dancer sits on the ''krae'' above two servants. (1928)]\n| image5 = [http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/42-17589854/traditional-cambodian-performers-dance-during-prayer-ceremony/ A dance of propitiation depicting the sea goddess Manimekhala. (2006)]\n| image6 = [http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/DWF15-974435/traditional-dancers-perform-for-new-cambodian-king/ Dancers perform for King Sihamoni's coronation. (2004)]\n}}\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n\n* Cravath, Paul (2008). ''Earth in Flower - The Divine Mystery of the Cambodian Dance Drama'', DatAsia Press\n* Groslier, George et al. (2011). ''Cambodian Dancers - Ancient and Modern'', DatAsia Press\n* Heywood, Denise (2009). ''Cambodian Dance Celebration of the Gods'', River Books\n* Loviny, Christophe (2003). ''The Apsaras of Angkor'', Sipar: Jazz Editions\n\n=== Fiction ===\n* Meyer, Charles (2009). ''Saramani: Cambodian Dance'', DatAsia Press\n* Lee, Jeanne M. (1994). ''Silent Lotus'', Farrar, Straus and Giroux\n* Lord, Michael (2006). ''Little Sap and Monsieur Rodin'', Lee & Low Books\n\n=== Selected discography ===\n* ''[[Musical Sources]] \u2013 Royal Music Of Cambodia'' (1971) by Jacques Brunet; contains a condensed recording of the ''Buong Suong'' dance drama featuring the goddess Manimekhala\n* ''Homrong: Classical Music From Cambodia'' (2004) by Chum Ngek; contains music pieces and suites used by the royal ballet\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Theatre of Cambodia]]\n* [[Dance in Cambodia]]\n*[[Apsara Dance|Robam Apsara]]\n*[[Robam Moni Mekhala]]\n*[[Robam Sovann Maccha]]\n* [[Dance in Thailand]]\n* ''[[Earth in Flower]]''\n* [[Khmer shadow theatre]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ich.unesco.org/en/news/cambodia-reorienting-its-methods-of-inventorying-living-heritage-00003|title=Cambodia reorienting its methods of inventorying living heritage - intangible heritage - Culture Sector - UNESCO|website=ich.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref>\n* [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ich.unesco.org/en/search-00795?q=Cambodia|title=Search within UNESCO ICH website - intangible heritage - Culture Sector - UNESCO|website=ich.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n\n* <span id=\"Banham1995\">Banham, Martin (1995). ''The Cambridge Guide to Theater'', Cambridge University Press</span>\n* <span id=\"Becker1998\">Becker, Elizabeth (1998). ''When the War Was Over: Cambodia and the Khmer Rouge Revolution'', PublicAffairs</span>\n* <span id=\"Bois\">Bois, George (1913). ''Les Danseuses cambodgiennes en France'', Imprimerie d'Extr\u00eame-Orient</span>\n* <span id=\"Bowers1956\">Bowers, Faubion. (1956). ''Theatre in the East'', New York T. Nelson</span>\n* <span id=\"Brandon1967\">Brandon, James R. (1967). ''Theatre in Southeast Asia''. Harvard University Press</span>\n* <span id=\"Cravath1968\">Cravath, Paul (1968). ''[https://www.jstor.org/pss/1124400 The Ritual Origins of the Classical Dance Drama of Cambodia]'', Asian Theatre Journal, Vol. 3, No. 2 (Autumn, 1986), pp.&nbsp;179\u2013203</span>\n* <span id=\"Fletcher2001\">Fletcher, Peter (2001). ''World Musics in Context: A Comprehensive Survey of the World's Major Musical Cultures'', Oxford University </span>\n* <span id=\"Jacobsen2008\">Jacobsen, Trudy (2008). ''Lost Goddesses: Denial of Female Power in Cambodian History'', Nordic Institute of Asian Studies</span>\n* <span id=\"Sasagawa2005\">Sasagawa, Hideo (2005). ''[https://kyoto-seas.org/pdf/42/4/420403.pdf Post/colonial Discourses on the Cambodian Court Dance]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'', Southeast Asian Studies, Vol. 42, No. 4, March 2005</span>\n* <span id=\"Falser2013\">Falser, Michael (2013). ''[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13527258.2013.794746 From a colonial reinvention to postcolonial heritage and a global commodity: performing and re-enacting Angkor Wat and the Royal Khmer Ballet]'', International Journal of Heritage Studies, May 2013</span>\n\n=== Notes ===\n''Notes in this section are referenced from the bibliography above.''\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n=== Unverified notes ===\n''Notes in this section reference material produced by laymen or reference material not generally considered a legitimate source on the subject matter at hand. They are unverified and not peer-reviewed.''\n<references group=\"unver.\" />\n\n== External links ==\n\n=== General information ===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050624083715/http://users.rcn.com/tskramer/dance.html Cambodian Classical Dance by Chamroeun Yin]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100316083812/http://www.devata.org/2009/06/nginn-karet-foundation-teaches-sacred-cambodian-dance-arts-at-banteay-srey-temple/ Nginn-Karet Foundation Teaches Sacred Dance at Banteay Srey]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100705230710/http://www.devata.org/2009/02/the-language-of-khmer-classical-dance-the-cambodia-daily/ The Language of Khmer Classical Dance | The Cambodia Daily]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130524154605/http://www.international.ucla.edu/cseas/article.asp?parentid=10982 The Near Extinction of Cambodian Classical Dance | UCLA Center for Southeast Asian Studies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110208233300/http://www.khmerdanceproject.com/ The Khmer Dance Project]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/27/arts/design/27rodi.html NY Times | Auguste Rodin and the Royal Ballet of Cambodia]\n* [http://khmerarts.org Khmer Arts | Founded by Sophiline Cheam Shapiro]\n\n=== Image galleries ===\n* [http://www.jiras.se/ Anders Jiras | Photography of Cambodian dance performances]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100210193958/http://www.earthinflower.com/eif.php?page=photo_gallery Earth in Flower | Photo gallery of 186 Cambodian dance photos arranged by chronology and topic]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110813022913/http://cambodiandancers.com/cd.php?page=photo_gallery Cambodian Dancers | Historical info and 169 original etchings from George Groslier's 1913 book ''Danseuses Cambodgiennes'']\n\n{{UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royal Ballet Of Cambodia}}\n[[Category:Asian dances]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Khmer classical dance|similar genera of performing arts|Lakhon khol|and|Lakhon pol srey}}\n{{Dance drama of Southeast Asia\n|image   = [[Image:Dancers angkor wat.jpg|200px]]\n|caption = The dancers of King Sisowath during a visit to the ruins of Angkor Wat\n}}\n{{Contains Khmer text}}\nThe '''Royal ballet of Cambodia ''' ({{lang-km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}} - ''Robam Preah Reachtroap'') is a form of performing arts established in the [[Court (royal)|royal courts]] of [[Cambodia]] for the purpose of entertainment as well as ceremonial [[propitiation]].<ref name=\"Cravath1968\">[[#Cravath1968|Cravath 1968]]</ref> It is the dominant genre of dance theatre in Cambodia that features the classical dance style ({{lang-km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e}} - ''Robam Kbach Boran'').\n\nIt is performed during [[Public holidays in Cambodia|public occasions]] and ceremonies in Cambodia as well as among Cambodians in other countries.<ref group=\"unver.\"> Public performances of Cambodian classical dance occasionally appear in Cambodian news and Western news outlets as photographs and video footage. See, for example, editorial photographs on Norodom Sihamoni's coronation at <http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/DWF15-974435/traditional-dancers-perform-for-new-cambodian-king/>.</ref> Performances entail elaborately dressed dancers performing a slow and figurative set of gestures and poses meant to entrance the viewer. The repertoire includes dances of tribute or [[invocation]] and the enactment of traditional stories and [[epic poems]] such as the ''[[Ramayana]]''.\n\n== Etymology ==\n\nWestern names for this dance tradition, such as '''Cambodian court dance''', often make reference to the royal court, as the tradition was performed and maintained by attendants of the royal palaces.<ref>[[#Banham1995|Banham 1995]], p. 154, \"performers were wives, concubines, and relatives of the ruler\"</ref><ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]], p. 59 \"Cambodian court dance\"</ref> As a performing art, it is formally referred to as the '''Royal Ballet of Cambodia''' (''le Ballet royal du Cambodge'' in French) by [[UNESCO]], Cravath, Brandon, and others in the academic field,<ref name=\"UNESCO\">[https://ich.unesco.org/en/RL/royal-ballet-of-cambodia-00060 UNESCO: Royal ballet of Cambodia - Intangible Heritage]</ref><ref>[[#Cravath1968|Cravath 1968]] mentions a variation: \"Royal Cambodian Ballet\".</ref><ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]] mentions \"Royal Cambodian Ballet\".</ref> although this term may also refer to the National Dance Company of Cambodia. The term '''Khmer classical dance''' is also used alongside \"Royal Ballet of Cambodia\" in publications by UNESCO and the above-mentioned authors.<ref name=\"UNESCO\"/>\n\nIn Khmer, it is formally known as ''Robam Preah Reach Trop'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}, lit. \"dances of royal wealth\") or ''Lakhon Preah Reach Trop'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}, lit. \"theatre of royal wealth\").<ref group=\"unver.\">UNESCO mentions ''lakhaon preah reach troap'', while it is also written as '\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799' (''robam preah reach trop'') on websites of the government of Cambodia, including the Ministry of Culture and Fine Arts. For example, see:<{{cite web |url=http://www.nwhc.cambodia.gov.kh/kh/node/136 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928150850/http://www.nwhc.cambodia.gov.kh/kh/node/136 |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}></ref> It is also referred to as ''Lakhon Luong'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u17a0\u17d2\u179b\u17bd\u1784}}, lit. \"the king's theatre\").<ref>[[#Cravath1968|Cravath]]; romanized as ''lakhon lueng'' (\"the king's dancers\")</ref><ref name=\"Fletcher2001\">[[#Fletcher2001|Fletcher 2001]], p. 306</ref> During the [[Cambodian coup of 1970|Lon Nol regime]] of Cambodia, the dance tradition was referred to as ''Lakhon Kbach Boran Khmer'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e\u1781\u17d2\u1798\u17c2\u179a}}, lit. \"Khmer theatre of the ancient style\"), a term alienating it from its royal legacy.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/><ref>[[#Sasagawa2005|Sasagawa 2005]], p. 437</ref>\n\nKhmer classical dancers, as a whole, are frequently referred to as ''apsara dancers'' by [[laymen]]; this usage would be incorrect with the modern form of the dance, as the ''apsara'' is just one type of character among others in the repertoire. Regardless, the tradition's romanticized affiliation with the ''apsaras'' and ''devatas'' of the ruins of [[Angkor]] still persists.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Finial with dancing figure from Cambodia, Angkorian style, 10th century, HAA.JPG|thumb|right|200px|[[Angkor]]ian style dancing figures from the 10th century]]\n[[File:LePetitJournal 1906 06 24.jpg|thumb|200px|The ''kinnari'' dancers of King Sisowath at the 1906 Colonial Exposition in Marseilles]]\n\n'''Angkor and pre-Angkor era'''\n\nOne of the earliest records of dance in Cambodia is from the 7th century, where performances were used as a funeral rite for kings.<ref>[[#Brandon1967|Brandon 1967]], p. 20</ref> In the 20th century, the use of dancers is also attested in funerary processions, such as that for King [[Sisowath Monivong]]. During the [[Angkor]] period, dance was ritually performed at temples.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The temple dancers came to be considered as apsaras, who served as entertainers and messengers to divinities.<ref>[[#Becker1998|Becker 1998]], p. 330</ref> Ancient stone inscriptions, describe thousands of apsara dancers assigned to temples and performing divine rites as well as for the public.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The tradition of temple dancers declined during the 15th century, as the Siamese kingdom of [[Ayutthaya Kingdom|Ayutthaya]] raided Angkor. When Angkor fell, its artisans, Brahmins, and dancers were taken captive to Ayutthaya.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/>\n\n'''French colonial era'''\n\nDancers of the court of [[Sisowath of Cambodia|King Sisowath]] were exhibited at the 1906 Colonial Exposition in [[Marseilles]] at the suggestion of George Bois, a French representative in the Cambodian court.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\">[[#Jacobsen2008|Jacobsen]], p. 156</ref> Auguste Rodin was captivated by the Cambodian dancers and painted a series of water colors of the dancers. George Groslier, the French-colonial director of the Phnom Penh Mus\u00e9e Sarraut (today the National Museum), had 're-invented' large parts of the ballet through his studies of the bas-reliefs of Angkor Wat.<ref name=\"Falser2013\">Falser 2013</ref>\n\n'''Post-independent Cambodia'''\n\nQueen [[Sisowath Kosamak|Sisowath Kossamak]] became a patron of the Royal Ballet of Cambodia. Under the Queen's guidance, several reforms were made to the royal ballet, including choreography. Dance dramas were dramatically shortened from all-night spectacles to about one hour in length.<ref name=\"Sasagawa 2005\">[[#Sasagawa2005|Sasagawa 2005]]</ref> Prince [[Norodom Sihanouk]] featured the dances of the royal ballet in his films. \n \nThe dance tradition suffered setbacks during the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime, during which many dancers were put to death in the genocide.<ref group=\"unver.\">jumpcut.com [http://www.jumpcut.com/view/?id=426CF07C3EC311DB93291EE329CBD869. ''Cambodian Royal Court Dancing'']. Retrieved July 21, 2007. {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Although 90 percent of all Cambodian classical artists perished between 1975 and 1979 after the fall of the Khmer Rouge, those who did survive wandered out from hiding, found one another, and formed \"colonies\" in order to revive their sacred traditions.<ref group=\"unver.\">Alliance for California Traditional Arts [http://www.actaonline.org/grants_and_programs/apprenticeships/1999/shapiro.htm ''Classical Cambodian Dance Sophiline Cheam Shapiro and Socheata Heng'']. Retrieved July 21, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708150335/http://www.actaonline.org/grants_and_programs/apprenticeships/1999/shapiro.htm |date=July 8, 2007 }}</ref> Khmer classical dance training was resurrected in the refugee camps in eastern Thailand with the few surviving Khmer dancers. Many dances and dance dramas were also recreated at the [[Royal University of Fine Arts]] in Cambodia.\n\nIn 2003 it was inducted into the [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists]].\n\n== Performance ==\n\n[[File:Royal Ballet Camboda Apsara Mera.jpg|thumb|right|The Royal Ballet of Cambodia at curtain call (Paris, France 2010)]]\n\nDuring the era of the [[French protectorate of Cambodia|French Protectorate of Cambodia]] and before, it was customary for guests of the royal palace to receive a performance of the royal ballet.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\" /> In propitiation ceremonies ({{lang|km|\u1794\u17bd\u1784\u179f\u17bd\u1784}}, ''{{transl|km|buong suong}}''), it was performed at [[Wat Phnom]] and the [[Silver Pagoda]] and Throne Hall of the [[Royal Palace, Phnom Penh|Royal Palace]].<ref group=\"unver.\">This can be noted in vintage photographs and film. UNESCO's video presentation of the Royal Ballet of Cambodia depicts a modern-day propitiation ceremony at Wat Phnom.</ref> For entertainment, performances were often staged inside the pavilions of royal palaces.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008\" /> In Phnom Penh, the Moonlight Pavilion was built for and is still used occasionally for classical dance performances. Nowadays, venues for performances by the Royal Ballet include the Chenla Theatre and the Chaktomuk Conference Hall, designed by architect [[Vann Molyvann]] during the [[Sangkum Reastr Niyum]] era.<ref group=\"unver.\">These venues have been mentioned on news reels on Cambodian news programs. See this article for an example: http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2011031447331/Lifestyle/discover-classic-dance-outdoors-by-chaktomuk.html</ref> Tourist restaurants in Cambodia, notably in [[Siem Reap]], also serve as venues for classical dance performances by amateur troupes.<ref group=\"unver.\">This can be seen in many photographs posted on Flickr and videos on Youtube. Restaurants include 'Jasmine Angkor' and 'Koulen'. Canby Publications has a section on this at <http://www.canbypublications.com/siemreap/srothersr.htm#PerformSR>.</ref>\n\n=== Stage and props ===\n\nThe traditional stage for classical dance drama performances contains a table with a decorative pillow, sometimes laid on an Oriental rug or carpet.<ref group=\"unver.\">As seen in this photograph: <https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5374895656/> and as depicted in other photographs and video.</ref> This table of low stature, called a ''krae'' ({{lang|km|\u1782\u17d2\u179a\u17c2}}, lit. \"bed\"), is constant throughout the performance and thus is used as a prop that represents many places and things (a bed, a throne, living quarters, etc.).<ref group=\"unver.\">Cravath romanizes this term as ''kr\u00e9''. In this photo of the Reamker [[:File:Cambodian dance Reamker.png]], parts of the ''krae'' can be seen behind the main group of dancers.</ref>\n\nIn many dance dramas, characters often wield weapons such as bows, swords, staves, and clubs.<ref group=\"unver.\">This is notable in many media provided by laymen online as well as photos provided in this article. See http://www.jiras.se/preahsamuth/index.html, which shows the dance drama Preah Samut and characters wielding bows and staves.</ref> In some dances, dancers hold items such as flower garlands, fans, and gold and silver flowers as a tribute (''see {{transl|ms|[[bunga mas]]}}'').<ref group=\"unver.\">See [File:Cambodian_Classical_Dance_of_Tribute.ogv] as an example where dancers hold gold flowers as a tribute.</ref> Performances of ''{{transl|km|robam makar}}'' (the [[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]] dance) entail devas dancing in leisure and using fans to represent the scales of the mythical makara while the goddess [[Manimekhala]] leads the mimicry with her crystal ball of magic.<ref group=\"unver.\">As seen in the Khmer classical dance video posted on this webpage: <http://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/dance/dance-spirit-cambodia> and many others.</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Cambodian_dance_Reamker.png|935px|A scene from the Reamker; a battle between Rama and Ravana performed in the courtyard of the Silver Pagoda, c. 1900s~1920s}}\n\n== Movement and gestures ==\n\nKhmer classical dancers use stylized movements and [[gesture]]s to convey meaning and tell a story. These gestures are often vague and abstract, though some may be easily understood. Dancers do not sing or generally speak, except in some dance dramas where there are brief instances of speech by the dancers.\n\nHand gestures in Khmer classical dance are called ''{{transl|km|kbach}}'' (meaning \"style\"). These hand gestures form a sort of alphabet and represent various things from nature such as fruit, flowers and leaves. They are used in different combinations and transitions with accompanying movement of the legs and feet to convey different thoughts and concepts.<ref name=\"Fletcher2001\"/> The way gestures are presented, the position of the arm, and the position of the hand relative to the arm can affect their meaning. Gestures are performed in different manners depending on the character type.\n\n== Characters ==\n\n[[File:BupphaDeviDance.png|thumb|Princess [[Buppha Devi]] performs a propitiation dance (c. 1965) as a ''{{transl|km|neang rong}}''. Note the dancers of lower ranks (''{{transl|km|philieng}}'') in [[obeisance]].]]\n\nFour main types of roles exist in Khmer classical dance: ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}'' (male), ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' (female), ''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' (ogres or [[asuras]]), and the ''{{transl|km|sva}}'' (monkeys).<ref name=\"Bois\">[[#Bois|Bois]], p. 4</ref> These four basic roles contain sub-classes to indicate character rank; a ''{{transl|km|neay rong ek}}'', for example, would be a leading male role and a ''{{transl|km|neang kamnan}}'' (or ''{{transl|km|philieng}}'') would be a maiden-servant.<ref name=\"Bois\"/> The sub-classes of the four main roles all perform in the same type of dancing style of the class they belong to. However, the ''{{transl|km|yeakheney}}'', or female ogre, is performed with a feminized dancing style of the male counterpart. Other female character types, such as the apsara, kinnari, or mermaid, follow the same dancing style as the ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' role but with subtle differences in gestures; the main difference being costume. The ''{{transl|km|ngoh}}'' character type, although male, is presented with a different dancing style than the ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}''.\n\nMost roles are performed by female dancers, but the role of monkeys was transferred to men under the guidance of Queen Sisowath Kosssamak. Other roles performed by men include hermits and animals such as horses and mythical lions.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n'''''{{transl|km|Neay rong}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neay rong ek}}'' - deities, kings, or princes (e.g. [[Rama]])\n*''{{transl|km|Philieng ek}}'' - ''aide-de-camp'' of important characters\n*''{{transl|km|Sena ek}}'' - the generals\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Neang}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neang ek}}'' - deities, queens or princesses (e.g. [[Sita]] and [[Manimekhala]])\n*''{{transl|km|Neang rong}}'' - [[noblewomen]] or angels (e.g., the daughters of the tycoon, Sampov Keo and Sampov Meas in the dance drama: ''{{transl|km|Krai Thong}}'')\n*''{{transl|km|Philieng ek}}'' - female ''aid-de-camp'' (ex. {{transl|km|Sopheak Leak}})\n*''{{transl|km|Neang kamnan}}'' or ''{{transl|km|philieng}}'' - female servants or attendants\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Yeak}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Yeak ek}}'' - premiere ogres or asuras (e.g., [[Ravana]])\n*''{{transl|km|Yeak rong}}'' - the lesser ogres\n*''{{transl|km|Yeakheney}}'' - ogresses, [[yakkhini]] (e.g. [[Surpanakha]])\n\n'''''{{transl|km|Sva}}'''''\n*''{{transl|km|Neay sva khen}}'' - monkey generals (e.g., [[Hanuman]])\n*''{{transl|km|Pouk khen sva}}'' - monkey soldiers\n\n'''Other character types'''\n*Apsaras - celestial nymphs\n*''{{transl|km|Kinnorey}}'' - the mythical [[kinnara|kinnaris]] (e.g. [[Manohara]])\n*''{{transl|km|Maccha}}'' - [[mermaid]]s (e.g., [[Suvannamaccha]])\n*''{{transl|km|Ngoh}}'' - a special masculine role depicting a [[negrito]]\n*''Eysey'' - hermits or [[rishi]], a non-dancing role\n*[[Porter (carrier)|Porters]] - involved loosely in the dance, generally does not dance\n\n'''Animals'''\n*[[Garuda]] and mythical birds (e.g. [[Jatayu]])\n*[[Deer]] - the Golden Deer in the ''Ramayana''\n*[[Peafowl]]\n*[[Lion]]s\n*[[Horse]]\n}}\n\n== Costume ==\n[[File:Apsara dance.jpg|thumb|right|[[Apsara]] dancer]]\nClassical dance costumes are highly ornate and heavily embroidered, sometimes including sequins and even semi-precious gems. Most of the costumes are thought to be representative of what divinities wear, as reflected in the art style of the post-Angkor period. Various pieces of the costume (such as shirts) have to be sewn onto the dancers for a tight fit.\n\n=== Female costume ===\n\nThe typical female, or ''{{transl|km|neang}}'', costume consists of a ''{{transl|km|[[sampot]] sarabap}}'' (or ''{{transl|km|charabap}}''), a type of woven fabric with two contrasting silk threads along with a metallic thread (gold or silver in color). The ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' is wrapped around the lower body in a sarong-like fashion, then [[pleated]] into a band in the front and secured with a gold or brass belt. In the current style, part of the pleated brocade band hangs over the belt on the left side of the belt buckle, which is a clear distinction from Thai classical dance costumes where this pleated band is tucked into the belt to the right of the belt buckle. Worn over the left shoulder is a [[shawl]]-like garment called a ''{{transl|km|[[sbai]]}}'' (also known as the ''{{transl|km|robang khnang}}'', literally \"back cover\"); it is the most decorative part of the female costume, embroidered extensively with tiny beads and sequins. The usual embroidery pattern for the ''sbai'' these days is a diamond-shaped floral pattern, but in the past there were more variations of floral patterns. Under the ''sbai'' is a silk undershirt or bodice worn with a short sleeve exposed on the left arm. Around the neck is an embroidered collar called a ''{{transl|km|srang kar}}''.\n\nJewelry for the female role includes a large, [[filigreed|filigree]] square pendant of which is hung by the corner, various types of ankle and wrists [[bracelets]] and [[bangle]]s, an [[arm ring|armlet]] on the right arm, and body chains of various styles.\n\n=== Male costume ===\n\nMale characters wear costumes that are more intricate than the females, as they require pieces, like sleeves, to be sewn together while being put on. They are dressed in a ''{{transl|km|sampot sarabap}}'' like their female counterpart; however, it is worn differently. For the male, or ''neay rong'', the ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' is worn in the ''{{transl|km|[[chang kben]]}}'' fashion, where the front is pleated and pulled under, between the legs, then tucked in the back and the remaining length of the pleat is stitched to the ''{{transl|km|sampot}}'' itself to form a draping 'fan' in the back. Knee-length pants are worn underneath, displaying a wide, embroidered [[hem]] around the knees. For the top, they wear long-sleeved shirts with rich embroidering, along with a collar, or ''{{transl|km|srang kar}}'', around their neck. On the end of their shoulders are a sort of [[epaulette]] that arches upwards like [[Indra]]'s bow (known as ''{{transl|km|inthanu}}''). Other components of the male costumes are three richly embroidered banners worn around the front waist. The center piece is known as a ''{{transl|km|robang muk}}'' while the two side pieces are known as a ''{{transl|km|cheay kraeng}}''; monkeys and yaksha characters wear another piece in the back called a ''{{transl|km|robang kraoy}}''.\n\nMale characters also wear an X-like strap around the body called a ''{{transl|km|sangvar}}''; it may be made of gold-colored silk or chains of gold with square ornaments, the latter being reserved for more important characters. Males wear the same ankle and wrist jewelry as females, but with the addition of an extra set of bangles on the wrist and no armlets. They also wear a kite-shaped ornament called a ''{{transl|km|sloek po}}'' (named after the [[bo tree]] leaf), which serves as a center point for their ''{{transl|km|sangvar}}''.\n\n=== Headdress ===\n\nThere are several types of [[Crown (headgear)|crowns]] that denote characters' ranks. Commonly worn by female characters of the lowest rank is the ''{{transl|km|kbang}}''; it is also worn by Brahmin characters with ornaments around a bun of hair. [[Divinity|Divinities]] and royal characters of the highest ranks wear a tall single-spire crown called a ''{{transl|km|mokot ksat}}'' for male characters and a ''{{transl|km|mokot ksatrey}}'' for female characters. The ''{{transl|km|panchuret}}'' (Groslier romanizes this as ''{{transl|km|panntiereth}}''), reserved for princes and generals (''{{transl|km|sena}}''), is a circlet-like crown with a faux knot in the back. The ''{{transl|km|rat klao}}'' is worn by princesses and often by maidens of significance in a dance if they happen to not be of royal rank. Some characters' headdressings include ear ornaments as well as earrings. Characters such as ogres and monkeys wear masks. Ogres and monkeys of royal rank wear masks with a ''{{transl|km|mokot}}'' attached.\n\n=== Floral adornments ===\n\nDancers are traditionally adorned with fragrant flowers, although sometimes fresh flowers are substituted with faux flowers. The floral tassel is traditionally made of ''[[Jasminum sambac]]'' strung together with ''[[Michelia]]'' flowers, being either ''[[Michelia \u00d7 alba]]'' or ''[[Michelia champaca]]''. The ''{{transl|km|neang}}'' (female) role wears a rose above the right ear and a floral tassel attached to the left side of the crown while the ''{{transl|km|neay rong}}'' (male) role wears a rose on the left ear and a floral tassel to the right side. Sometimes, dancers will wear jasmine garlands fit for the wrists. The ''apsara'' role is most often adorned with the flowers of either ''[[Plumeria obtusa]]'' or white cultivars of ''[[Plumeria rubra]]''; sometimes plumerias are tied along the back of their hair.\n\n== Music ==\n{{main|Pinpeat}}\n{{listen \n | filename     = Khmer classical dance song.ogg\n | title        = Krai Thong\n | description  = A song from a scene in the dance drama Krai Thong.\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\n\nThe music used for Khmer classical dance is played by a pinpeat ensemble. This type of orchestra consists of several types of [[xylophones]], [[drum]]s, [[oboe]]s, [[gong]]s, and other [[musical instrument]]s. The chorus consists of several singers who mainly sing in the absence of music. The lyrics are in poetry form and are sung interspersed with the grammatical particles eu [\u0259\u02d0], eung [\u0259\u02d0\u014b], and euy [\u0259\u02d0j] in various patterns.\n\n=== Musical instruments ===\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat ek]]}}'' : The lead xylophone with bamboo or teak wood keys\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat thung]]}}'' : A xylophone with bamboo or teak wood keys; low\n*''{{transl|km|[[Roneat dek]]}}'' : A metallophone of brass keys\n*''{{transl|km|Roneat thong}}'' : A metallophone (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|[[Kong thom]]}}'' : A set of 16 gongs arranged in a circle\n*''{{transl|km|[[Kong toch]]}}'' : Like the gongs above, but smaller\n*''{{transl|km|[[Chhing]]}}'' : A pair of finger cymbals\n*''{{transl|km|Krap}}'' : A pair of wood clappers (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|[[Sralai]]}}'' : A type of shawm; there are two sizes\n*''{{transl|km|[[Khloy]]}}'' : A type of flute made from bamboo (now rarely used)\n*''{{transl|km|Skor thom}}'' : A pair of drums played with a percussion mallet\n*''{{transl|km|[[Sampho]]}}'' : A type of drum played with the hands\n}}\n\n=== Music pieces ===\nKhmer classical dance uses particular pieces of music for certain events, such as when a dancer enters or leaves a scene, or performs certain actions, such as flying or walking. These musical pieces are arranged to form a suite. New pieces of music are rarely created.\n\nBelow is a select list of music pieces used in the repertoire:\n\n*''{{transl|km|Sathukar}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17b6\u1792\u17bb\u1780\u17b6\u179a}}) a song of blessing used for [[propitiation]], often used to commence a performance\n*''{{transl|km|Krao nai}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179a\u17c5\u178e\u17c3}}), also known as ''{{transl|km|santheuk knong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u1793\u17d2\u1792\u17b9\u1780\u1780\u17d2\u1793\u17bb\u1784}}), overture of the ''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' (ogre) characters, a display of power as they go into [[combat]] or battle\n*''{{transl|km|Smaeu}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17d2\u1798\u17be}}) used for the introduction of a character or a group of dancers in a scene\n*''{{transl|km|Lea}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17b6}}) used to present a character's departure from the scene; leaving the [[stage (theatre)|stage]]\n*''{{transl|km|Cheut chhing}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1787\u17be\u178f\u1788\u17b7\u1784}}) lit., [[euphonic]] ''{{transl|km|[[chhing]]}}''; music characterized by the constant percussion of drums and small cup-shaped cymbals;<ref group=\"unver.\">Robert K. Headley 1997, ''Cambodian-English Dictionary''</ref> used to present an action such as commencing a journey or flying\n*''{{transl|km|Lo}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17c4}}) music used in tune with aquatic recreation (e.g. dancers miming the action of [[Watercraft rowing|rowing a boat]])\n*''{{transl|km|Long song mon}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179b\u1784\u179f\u17ca\u1784\u1798\u1793}}) lit., \"royal bathing of the [[Mon people|Mon]]\"; a song used to represent a character dressing up their appearance\n*''{{transl|km|Phya deun}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1795\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u178c\u17be\u1793}}); also known as ''{{transl|km|ponhea daeur}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u1789\u17d2\u1789\u17b6\u178a\u17be\u179a}}), a music piece used to present dancers marching (e.g. the beginning of ''{{transl|km|robam tep monorom}}'')\n*''{{transl|km|Klom}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179b\u17bb\u1798}}) used to show the grace and beauty of a character wielding his weapon\n*''{{transl|km|Sinuon}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17ca\u17b8\u1793\u17bd\u1793}}) - lit., \"cream color\", in reference to complexion, a soft and slow feminine melody\n*''{{transl|km|Salamar}}'' : ({{lang|km|\u179f\u179b\u1798\u17b6\u179a}}) - a music characterized by the ''{{transl|km|sralai}}'', often used for certain actions such as combat, but not limited to such\n*''{{transl|km|Preah Thong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u1790\u17c4\u1784}})\n*''{{transl|km|Bao Lut}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1794\u17c4\u179b\u17bb\u178f}})\n*''{{transl|km|Sarak Burong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u179a\u17c8\u1794\u17ca\u17bb\u179a\u1784}})\n*''{{transl|km|Balim}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1794\u179b\u17b7\u1798}})\n\n== Repertoire ==\n\nAccording to ''The Cambridge Guide to Asian Theatre'' (1997), the Royal Ballet's repertoire contained approximately 40 dances and 60 dance dramas. Since the restoration of the Royal Ballet in the 1979, some of the old repertoire was recreated and several new dances were also created, most notably ''robam monosanhchettana'' by the late Chea Samy. As of recent years, new dance dramas have been created by the Royal Ballet, such as ''Apsara Mera''. [[Sophiline Cheam Shapiro]] has also introduced new repertory to Khmer classical dance, although they are not part of the traditional royal repertoire and mainly have been performed in Western venues. Her works include dramas such as ''{{transl|km|Samritechak}}'', an adaptation of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Othello]]'' and ''{{transl|km|Pamina Devi}}'', an adaptation of [[Mozart]]'s ''[[The Magic Flute]]''.\n\n=== Dance dramas ===\n\nThe repertoire of dance dramas ({{lang|km|\u179a\u17bf\u1784}}, ''{{transl|km|roeung}}'') consists of a myriad of stories, unlike the ''{{transl|km|lakhon khol}}'', which is limited only to the ''Ramayana''. Many of the dance dramas have analogs in the ''lakhon nai'' dance genre of Thailand but do not share the same choreography or exact storyline. During the time of Queen Kossamak, several dance dramas were re-choreographed and shortened such as ''[[Preah Thong and Neang Neak|Roeung Preah Thong-Neang Neak]]''; this drama, among others, would be recreated in 2003.\n\nThe plots of many dance dramas often concern a male character who rescues a [[damsel in distress]] or destined love presented with obstacles. The traditional repertoire portrays mythology or traditional tales and may sometimes include religious concepts such as [[karma]].\n\n[[File:Cambodian Classical Dance of Tribute.ogv|thumb|400px|A dance of tribute used in a dance drama titled ''Preah Ket Mealea'', circa 1965]]\n\n==== Select repertory of dance dramas ====\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''{{transl|km|[[Reamker]]}}'' (''Ramakerti'', {{lang|km|\u179a\u17b6\u1798\u1780\u17c1\u179a\u17d2\u178f\u17b7\u17cd}}): Ramayana\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Sothon-Neang Monorea}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u17bc\u1792\u1793-\u1793\u17b6\u1784\u1798\u1793\u17c4\u17a0\u17cd\u179a\u17b6}}): Sudhana-Jataka, formerly referred to as ''{{transl|km|Kailas}} ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17c3\u179b\u17b6\u179f}}), recreated in 2003\n* ''{{transl|km|Krai Thong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1790\u17c4\u1784}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Inao}}'' ({{lang|km|\u17a5\u178e\u17b6\u179c}}): [[Panji (prince)|Panji]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Kakey}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17b6\u1780\u17b8}}): Kakati-Jataka\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Anoruth-Neang Usa}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u17a2\u1793\u17bb\u179a\u17bb\u1791\u17d2\u1792-\u1793\u17b6\u1784\u17a7\u179f\u17b6}}): [[Aniruddha]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Sopheak Leak}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17bb\u1797\u179b\u1780\u17d2\u1781\u178e\u17cd}}): [[Chitralekha (deity)|Chitralekha]]\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Samot}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u1798\u17bb\u1791\u17d2\u179a}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Sovannahong}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17bb\u179c\u178e\u17d2\u178e\u17a0\u1784\u17d2\u179f}})\n* ''{{transl|km|Preah Sang}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179f\u17d0\u1784\u17d2\u1781}})\n}}\n\n=== Dances ===\n\nIn contrast to the dance dramas are shorter dances known as ''{{transl|km|robam}}''. They can serve several purposes, such as honoring, ritualistic functions (e.g. securing the kingdom's fortune and prosperity), and blessing. Spanning several minutes or so, not all these dances have storylines, although many ''robam'' are indeed excerpts from dance dramas such as ''{{transl|km|robam mekhala-reamso}}'' and ''{{transl|km|robam sovan macchha}}'' (the latter being from the ''{{transl|km|Reamker}}'').\n\nThe 'apsara dance' of today was created under the guidance of Queen Kossamak Nearireath. Its costume is based on the [[bas-relief]] of ''apsaras'' on temple ruins but much of it, including its music and gesture, is not unique from other classical Khmer dances that probably do not date back to the [[Angkor]] period.\n\n==== Select repertory of dances ====\n\n* [[Apsara Dance|Robam Apsara]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u17a2\u1794\u17d2\u179f\u179a\u17b6)\n* [[Robam Tep Monorom]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1791\u17c1\u1796\u1798\u1793\u17c4\u179a\u1798\u17d2\u1799)\n* [[Robam Chun Por]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1787\u17bc\u1793\u1796\u179a)\n* [[Robam Makar]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1798\u1780\u179a)\n* [[Robam Sovann Maccha]] (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u179f\u17bb\u179c\u178e\u17d2\u178e\u1798\u1785\u17d2\u1786\u17b6)\n* [[Robam Moni Mekhala]] or Mekhala-Reamesor (\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1798\u178e\u17b8\u1798\u17c1\u1781\u179b\u17b6)\n\n== Glossary ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n;''{{transl|km|kbach}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785}}) : (lit., \"style\" or \"motif\") referring to a pose or gesture used in Khmer classical dance\n;''{{transl|km|lakhon}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793}}) : (lit., \"theatre\"; also romanized as ''lakhaon'' and ''lkhaon''), referring to different genres of theatrical performances\n;''{{transl|km|lakhon preah reach trop}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179b\u17d2\u1781\u17c4\u1793\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c7\u179a\u17b6\u1787\u1791\u17d2\u179a\u1796\u17d2\u1799}}): (lit., \"theatre of royal wealth\") the Khmer name for the main classical dance drama of Cambodia; the royal ballet of Cambodia, in this case, the term ''lakhon'' may be substituted with ''robam''\n;''{{transl|km|robam}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6}}) : (lit., \"dance\"), a term used to refer to dances and in some contexts, all classical dances\n;''{{transl|km|robam kbach boran}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u1794\u17b6\u17c6\u1780\u17d2\u1794\u17b6\u1785\u17cb\u1794\u17bc\u179a\u17b6\u178e}}): (lit., \"dance of the ancient style\") a term referring to classical dance that is used in the genres of theatre including ''{{transl|km|lakhon khol}}'', ''{{transl|km|lakhon pol srey}}'', and ''{{transl|km|lakhon preah reach trop}}''. Not to be confused with the term devised in the Lon Nol era.\n;''{{transl|km|roeung}}'' ({{lang|km|\u179a\u17c0\u1784}}) : (lit., \"story\"); referring to dance dramas\n;''{{transl|km|yeak}}'' ({{lang|km|\u1799\u1780\u17d2\u1781}}) : [[yaksha]]; a class of characters representing [[asuras]] and [[ogres]], commonly translated as \"giants\"\n}}\n\n== Media ==\n\n=== Gallery ===\n{{Commons category multi|Khmer classical dance|Royal Ballet of Cambodia}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:BupphaDeviDancing.png|Princess Buppha Devi performs a dance\nFile:Thais return Battambang to King Sisowath.jpg|A depiction of the ancient ''apsara'' costume (left maiden) and the Siamese-influenced costume (center maiden)\nFile:Indra Silver Pagoda Mural.jpg|A mural depicting Indra and his dancers\nFile:Cambodiacourtdance.gif\n</gallery>\n\n{{ external media\n| align  = right\n| image1 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5630277276/ Two dancers perform as a garuda and kinnari couple. (1928)]\n| image2 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5374895656/ A pair of dancers sit on a ''krae''. (1931)]\n| image3 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5629694471/ Ravana with Sita in his captive. (1928)]\n| image4 = [https://www.flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/5630278044/ A dancer sits on the ''krae'' above two servants. (1928)]\n| image5 = [http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/42-17589854/traditional-cambodian-performers-dance-during-prayer-ceremony/ A dance of propitiation depicting the sea goddess Manimekhala. (2006)]\n| image6 = [http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/DWF15-974435/traditional-dancers-perform-for-new-cambodian-king/ Dancers perform for King Sihamoni's coronation. (2004)]\n}}\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n\n* Cravath, Paul (2008). ''Earth in Flower - The Divine Mystery of the Cambodian Dance Drama'', DatAsia Press\n* Groslier, George et al. (2011). ''Cambodian Dancers - Ancient and Modern'', DatAsia Press\n* Heywood, Denise (2009). ''Cambodian Dance Celebration of the Gods'', River Books\n* Loviny, Christophe (2003). ''The Apsaras of Angkor'', Sipar: Jazz Editions\n\n=== Fiction ===\n* Meyer, Charles (2009). ''Saramani: Cambodian Dance'', DatAsia Press\n* Lee, Jeanne M. (1994). ''Silent Lotus'', Farrar, Straus and Giroux\n* Lord, Michael (2006). ''Little Sap and Monsieur Rodin'', Lee & Low Books\n\n=== Selected discography ===\n* ''[[Musical Sources]] \u2013 Royal Music Of Cambodia'' (1971) by Jacques Brunet; contains a condensed recording of the ''Buong Suong'' dance drama featuring the goddess Manimekhala\n* ''Homrong: Classical Music From Cambodia'' (2004) by Chum Ngek; contains music pieces and suites used by the royal ballet\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Theatre of Cambodia]]\n* [[Dance in Cambodia]]\n*[[Apsara Dance|Robam Apsara]]\n*[[Robam Moni Mekhala]]\n*[[Robam Sovann Maccha]]\n* [